WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
[Amit Varma]: One question that all of us have asked ourselves about our own lives is the question, what

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:12.240
[Amit Varma]: if?

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:14.400
[Amit Varma]: What if I had done this instead of that?

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:16.360
[Amit Varma]: What if I had chosen another career?

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:20.760
[Amit Varma]: What if I had lived in a different city or not gone on that first date, or was just born

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:22.440
[Amit Varma]: in a different family?

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:23.440
[Amit Varma]: What if?

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:26.820
[Amit Varma]: There's a universe of possibilities in just those words.

00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:30.980
[Amit Varma]: And our fascination with those words extends beyond our own lives.

00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:32.700
[Amit Varma]: What if the world was a different place?

00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:36.160
[Amit Varma]: We apply this to history sometimes, and that can be a mistake.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:40.840
[Amit Varma]: The world is complex, but we tell ourselves simple stories to make sense of it.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:46.520
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, the past has many layers, and we build simple histories to make sense of it.

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:51.080
[Amit Varma]: For this reason, what if questions often don't work?

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:55.720
[Amit Varma]: Changing one variable in a complex world may not change much at all.

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:58.560
[Amit Varma]: But what if that variable is a big variable?

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.880
[Amit Varma]: What if that variable is a Mughal emperor?

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:05.760
[Amit Varma]: If a tolerant and intellectually curious religious scholar had become Mughal emperor instead

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:10.660
[Amit Varma]: of an orthodox, bigoted, violent man, would history have proceeded differently?

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:15.360
[Amit Varma]: If Dara Shikoh had become emperor instead of his younger brother Aurangzeb, would India

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:32.320
[Unknown]: be a different place today?

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:33.800
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:38.740
[Amit Varma]: My guest on the show today, the historian Supriya Gandhi, once said that she saw one

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:41.920
[Amit Varma]: of her tasks as making history complex again.

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:46.440
[Amit Varma]: While the pursuit of history might be driven by the need to build narratives that explain

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:50.960
[Amit Varma]: the world, and those narratives are always simpler than the real world, it could be argued

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:55.560
[Amit Varma]: that the stories we have of the past today in India are just too damn simple.

00:01:55.560 --> 00:01:59.920
[Amit Varma]: Such as the one I mentioned a few moments ago about Dara Shikoh and Aurangzeb.

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:03.600
[Amit Varma]: We like to think of them in the stark binaries I mentioned.

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Dara as a tolerant and intellectually curious religious scholar, and Aurangzeb as a brutal

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:09.920
[Amit Varma]: bigot.

00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:15.360
[Amit Varma]: But these are caricatures, and both men were far more complex than these glib descriptions

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:16.680
[Amit Varma]: can capture.

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:22.920
[Amit Varma]: Another false binary is the one between tolerant Sufism and rigid orthodox Islam.

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:28.160
[Amit Varma]: Also a simplistic view that misses the complexities of Islam in India.

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:32.960
[Amit Varma]: To better understand those complexities, I recommend you read The Emperor Who Never Was

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:36.080
[Amit Varma]: Dara Shikoh in Mughal India by Supriya Gandhi.

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:40.800
[Amit Varma]: This is a marvellous human portrait of Dara Shikoh that gives a deep sense of what a complex

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:45.680
[Amit Varma]: man he was, and which also shows us the complex times he lived in.

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:50.000
[Amit Varma]: There is a popular narrative today that talks about how India would be so different if Dara

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.160
[Amit Varma]: had been emperor instead of Aurangzeb.

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:57.320
[Amit Varma]: Ashok Malik even called the murder of Dara Shikoh, quote, the partition before partition,

00:02:57.320 --> 00:02:58.320
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:02.700
[Amit Varma]: Supriya's book gives me the sense that, well, maybe we are overthinking it.

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:05.260
[Amit Varma]: Maybe it won't have been that different.

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:09.080
[Amit Varma]: And certainly we would all still have been coping with lockdown.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:16.240
[Amit Varma]: Before we head on over to the conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

