[Amit Varma]: sceneunseen.in slash support Supriya, welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:37.640
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Pleasure to be here.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.960
[Amit Varma]: Before we begin, you know, I'd like to know a little bit about your sort of intellectual

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:45.720
[Amit Varma]: and academic journey.

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:47.840
[Amit Varma]: Like how did you get into the field that you are in?

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:51.500
[Amit Varma]: You majored in religious studies, you teach religious studies at Yale.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, what drew you to this field?

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:59.360
[Amit Varma]: And who was sort of your intellectual influences while you were growing as an intellectual?

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:05.680
[Guest]: Religious studies is a field that is far more commonly encountered in the United States.

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:11.240
[Guest]: And it's sometimes confused with theology or divinity studies.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:13.560
[Guest]: Religious studies is studying about religion.

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:17.080
[Guest]: It isn't comparing religions to see what the best religion is.

00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:22.840
[Guest]: Neither is it training people to become priests or chaplains or whatever.

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:31.320
[Guest]: And I actually haven't really studied religion very much formally.

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:38.080
[Guest]: But my interest in this and my whole intellectual trajectory was shaped by growing up in India.

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:43.600
[Guest]: I changed schools a number of times, I went to a boarding school.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:48.600
[Guest]: And then finally, when I turned 17, I landed in Delhi to go to college, I went to St. Stephen's

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:49.600
[Guest]: College.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:55.240
[Guest]: And for me, my educational experience wasn't just the college and the people I encountered

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:59.320
[Guest]: there and my teachers, of course, that they were also very important.

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:05.160
[Guest]: It was exploring an Indian city as an adult, especially a city like Delhi with all the

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:14.680
[Guest]: layers of history and histories of people, migrations, etc., associated with it.

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:18.160
[Guest]: So I would enjoy exploring Old Delhi.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:25.720
[Guest]: And one day I came across near Ajmeri Gate, the Ghazi-ud-Din Madrasa, which seemed to

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:27.760
[Guest]: be just a beautiful building.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:30.880
[Guest]: It was utterly quiet, full of the sound of birds.

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:34.280
[Guest]: And I was there with a couple of friends and we just started wandering around.

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:36.080
[Guest]: And then we were accosted by somebody.

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.400
[Guest]: And I thought he was going to tell us off, that he was going to rebuke us and say, get

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:41.400
[Guest]: out of here.

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:46.760
[Guest]: And instead, he said, he asked if we had come to see Dr. Joffrey.

00:06:46.760 --> 00:06:49.640
[Guest]: And at that point, I wasn't quite sure who he was.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:54.240
[Guest]: And then he introduced himself as Dr. Yunus Joffrey, the Persian professor, and no doubt

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:57.880
[Guest]: he was very used to having all kinds of people making a pilgrimage to see him.

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:02.520
[Guest]: And it turned out he'd been profiled in William Dalrymple's book, City of Djinns.

00:07:02.520 --> 00:07:08.880
[Guest]: So Dr. Joffrey invited us to his little room, his little cell, and he served us delicious

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:11.640
[Guest]: chai and offered to teach us Persian.

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:17.960
[Guest]: And I was the only one among our friends who took him up on the offer and I started learning

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:19.520
[Guest]: the alphabet.

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:24.520
[Guest]: And I thought this would be a wonderful opportunity to read the poetry of Rumi, about whom I'd

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:25.520
[Guest]: heard, of course.

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:34.400
[Guest]: So with Dr. Joffrey and my explanations of Delhi, I got my initial introduction into

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:42.040
[Guest]: a language and a history that was very, very much part of the education of most educated

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:48.520
[Guest]: people in North India at one point in time, but that had been excised from my own curriculum.

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:55.920
[Guest]: So it was a fascinating complement to my studies of philosophy, which I pursued at St. Stephen's.

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:01.400
[Guest]: And I had an equal interest in Indian philosophy, Sanskrit philosophy, the Sikh Darshanas, and

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:03.840
[Guest]: so on.

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:09.400
[Guest]: And after this, after my studies, I was going to either spend a year in Benares doing Sanskrit

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:12.160
[Guest]: or spend a year in Iran doing Persian.

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:15.360
[Guest]: And the year in Iran worked out, so I landed up there.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:17.200
[Guest]: I wanted to do something different.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:24.160
[Guest]: It's quite common for people from my college to, if they got good marks and so on, to want

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:28.520
[Guest]: to go to Oxford and Cambridge, and that idea didn't really attract me.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:35.080
[Guest]: I wanted to do something that didn't really have so much to do with an education in the

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:37.640
[Guest]: West, not immediately.

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:41.600
[Guest]: So that year in Iran led to lots of other things.

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:43.840
[Guest]: I was immersed in the study of Persian.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:51.640
[Guest]: I got to see a fascinating side of Iran that isn't really covered in the Western press.

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:58.760
[Guest]: Studying in India is a huge advantage, just immense hospitality and warmth that I received

00:08:58.760 --> 00:08:59.760
[Guest]: over there.

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:05.080
[Guest]: And I got to see this amazing, very vibrant intellectual culture, some of it underground,

00:09:05.080 --> 00:09:11.040
[Guest]: some of it not so much, this long street of books in Taiwan that is probably one of the

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:17.640
[Guest]: longest streets for bookshops in the world, students discussing philosophy and ideas,

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:20.760
[Guest]: an immense amount of intellectual curiosity.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:26.520
[Guest]: So what I wanted to do then was to take what I had learned in Iran of the Persian language,

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:32.760
[Guest]: philosophy, Sufism, and so on, and apply that back to India, because then I discovered that

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:36.920
[Guest]: there were all these texts that were waiting to be read.

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:41.320
[Guest]: I started hearing about Raghunath Shukla, although I didn't know that I was later going

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:47.480
[Guest]: to work on him, and all the Persian translations of Sanskrit works at Akbar's court and so

00:09:47.480 --> 00:09:48.480
[Guest]: on.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:53.760
[Guest]: So I had the skill, and I might as well put it to use, but not just yet.

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:55.920
[Guest]: So I continued my studies.

00:09:55.920 --> 00:10:01.640
[Guest]: I got a master's degree in London in Middle Eastern studies, and I started Arabic.

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:09.040
[Guest]: I spent a year in Syria, I spent a year immersing myself in Arabic and the study of the Islamic

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:11.120
[Guest]: sciences through Arabic.

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:18.000
[Guest]: And that was very, very different Syria to the war-torn, ravaged country that it is now

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:19.000
[Guest]: now.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.640
[Guest]: So that also was a wonderful experience.

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:26.760
[Guest]: And then I realized that I had to pursue a PhD in the United States, where you have the

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:34.320
[Guest]: advantage of being able to fund your studies, you get paid to study and teach if you get

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:35.320
[Guest]: admission.

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:41.440
[Guest]: So that's what I did, and so that's where I've ended up now.

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:50.560
[Guest]: So my PhD was really in area studies, but I ended up working on topics that give me

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:56.400
[Guest]: a common vocabulary and common interests with those in the study of religion.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:57.840
[Amit Varma]: So that's where I've ended up right now.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:01.960
[Amit Varma]: So you know, it's fascinating that you often warned against looking at, you know, history

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:05.360
[Amit Varma]: in terms of simple narratives, but you know, while you were telling the story, it almost

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:10.440
[Amit Varma]: seemed as if it if it wasn't for that serendipitous meeting with Dr. Joffrey in the ruins and

00:11:10.440 --> 00:11:14.840
[Amit Varma]: him offering to sort of teach you Persian, this whole journey may not have happened.

00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:15.840
[Amit Varma]: Is that kind of true?

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:21.880
[Amit Varma]: Or did you have a prior interest in all of these areas anyway, in terms of history and,

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:23.880
[Guest]: you know, languages and so on?

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:24.880
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:30.680
[Guest]: Well, you know, it's a little hard to go back and do a counterfactual autobiography to see

00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:33.840
[Guest]: what might have happened had I not met Dr. Joffrey.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:43.120
[Guest]: But I think my interest in exploring Old Delhi did stem from my curiosity about, about these

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:48.880
[Guest]: aspects that at least one part of my own school curriculum, and that were very much part of

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:52.640
[Guest]: my exploring the city around me.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:53.640
[Amit Varma]: So it might have happened.

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:58.200
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, did you sort of have a specific vision of yourself in the future

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:02.120
[Amit Varma]: that I want to study history or write books of history or so on?

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:05.880
[Amit Varma]: Or were you just sort of going with your passions and going with your interests and letting

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:07.640
[Guest]: them lead you where they would?

00:12:07.640 --> 00:12:11.680
[Guest]: I had no specific career plans.

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:18.200
[Guest]: My boarding school was founded by J. Krishnamurti, it was in South India, and we were encouraged

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:20.640
[Guest]: to do things for the sake of it.

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:25.320
[Guest]: It wasn't like kind of typical Indian school with rankings and like people having people

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:27.600
[Guest]: really eager to do competitive exams.

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:32.160
[Guest]: Of course, one's very lucky and privileged to be to be free of that.

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:40.520
[Guest]: But no, I was I was not thinking instrumentally in any way I was following my interests.

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:45.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, it sort of strikes me that, you know, did studying Persian and did for

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:50.720
[Amit Varma]: example, spending time in Iran and Syria and all of that, give you a window into aspects

00:12:50.720 --> 00:12:55.440
[Amit Varma]: of India and Indian culture, which are otherwise invisible to us, for example, we know that

00:12:55.440 --> 00:13:00.280
[Amit Varma]: there is a lot of Persian influence in our language, in our culture, in our cooking and

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:05.160
[Amit Varma]: all of that, except that is, you know, we've internalized it and we don't think of ourselves

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:06.160
[Amit Varma]: in that way.

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:09.320
[Amit Varma]: Many of us don't think of ourselves as the sort of melting pot that we are where all

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:11.140
[Amit Varma]: these influences exist.

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:15.760
[Amit Varma]: So did you feel that your understanding of India itself, our culture, our language, all

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:21.720
[Amit Varma]: of that deepened because you were going deeper into say, the influences of Persian as a language

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:27.040
[Amit Varma]: and then maybe influences from Iran as a culture because those exist as well?

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:31.560
[Amit Varma]: Did that make you sort of see the unseen, in a sense, which many of us would otherwise

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:32.560
[Guest]: miss out on?

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:33.560
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:34.560
[Guest]: I think definitely.

00:13:34.560 --> 00:13:40.200
[Guest]: So and you know, I consider myself very much still a student of India and Indian history,

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:42.280
[Guest]: you know, I find it endlessly fascinating.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:48.800
[Guest]: Yes, my studies of Persian, for instance, helped me see all the Persian words that existed

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:57.880
[Guest]: in Hindustani and Indian languages, the influences, whether it's cuisine, poetry, language, and

00:13:57.880 --> 00:13:58.880
[Guest]: so on.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:02.880
[Guest]: You know, had I grown up in Lucknow, for instance, you know, I might have been more steeped in

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:08.000
[Guest]: that, but I spent a lot of my life in South India and in, you know, in fairly, you know,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
[Guest]: insulated environments.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:15.160
[Guest]: So absolutely, I got a completely different perspective on India, through my studies in

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:16.600
[Amit Varma]: Iran and in Syria.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:20.800
[Amit Varma]: And is it sort of, you know, when you start studying history, given that, especially when

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:25.200
[Amit Varma]: you study the Mughals, right, there are such set narratives about the Mughals that are

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:26.480
[Amit Varma]: already there.

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:30.600
[Amit Varma]: And when you, you know, start studying a period in history, how difficult is it to put the

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:32.480
[Amit Varma]: hindsight bias away?

00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:33.720
[Amit Varma]: Because there's no mystery, right?

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:39.080
[Amit Varma]: We already know everything that has happened in terms of the events that have taken place.

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:43.200
[Amit Varma]: And for those specific times, there are very few sources, often those sources will tend

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:47.560
[Amit Varma]: to be biased sources, like the winners will write their own history, and Aurangzeb obviously

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:52.360
[Amit Varma]: will want to, you know, paint Dara Shikoh in whatever way is convenient to him.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:57.640
[Amit Varma]: So how difficult is it to then be able to say that, you know, regardless of what period

00:14:57.640 --> 00:15:01.480
[Amit Varma]: of history you're studying, how difficult is it to sort of strip all of that away the

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:06.880
[Amit Varma]: things that you know, the narratives that are almost reflexive to us, and be able to

00:15:06.880 --> 00:15:11.440
[Amit Varma]: sort of figure out things in a contemporary way, like one of the things that struck me

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:16.080
[Amit Varma]: while reading your book, which was so different from everything that we've sort of learned

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:19.800
[Amit Varma]: about Dara Shikoh and Aurangzeb, apart from obviously the false binaries, which we'll

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:20.920
[Amit Varma]: discuss later.

00:15:20.920 --> 00:15:25.200
[Amit Varma]: But one of the things that kind of struck me was that sense throughout the book that

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:30.920
[Amit Varma]: Dara Shikoh is really in training to be an emperor, it's it's almost it seems foredeigned

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:35.080
[Amit Varma]: and he is behaving as if he is going to be the emperor, he's almost co ruling with his

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:36.760
[Amit Varma]: father in a sense.

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:41.480
[Amit Varma]: And then one day it all falls apart and Aurangzeb is a, you know, a bit player in all of this

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:44.520
[Amit Varma]: going off to the deck and going off there going off here.

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:48.920
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when we typically look at history, we think of what we're taught in our textbooks,

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:52.400
[Amit Varma]: these are the great emperors, you know, after Shah Jahan, there's Aurangzeb and it's a very

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:53.400
[Amit Varma]: different look.

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:54.400
[Amit Varma]: So how do you do that?

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:58.660
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you have to consciously tell yourself that look, I have to avoid these

00:15:58.660 --> 00:16:03.360
[Amit Varma]: dominant narratives, I have to, you know, look at each period and each event as if I

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.560
[Amit Varma]: don't know what is happening next?

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:07.640
[Guest]: Is that a discipline you have to build?

00:16:07.640 --> 00:16:09.560
[Guest]: That's an interesting question.

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:16.280
[Guest]: And actually, to an extent, that is sort of the methodology that I've followed in this

00:16:16.280 --> 00:16:17.280
[Guest]: book.

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:21.920
[Guest]: Initially, I was, I was reluctant to choose Dara Shikoh, partly because he's so well known.

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:24.400
[Guest]: He's not as well known as Aurangzeb.

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:30.680
[Guest]: But the story of Dara Shikoh and Aurangzeb is sort of like a foundational origin story

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:35.960
[Guest]: of the subcontinent explaining how we got where we are today.

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:38.200
[Guest]: So I was a bit hesitant about doing that.

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:42.880
[Guest]: Because there's also a lot of merit in looking at the histories of people who don't have

00:16:42.880 --> 00:16:43.880
[Guest]: written histories.

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:49.880
[Guest]: There are many, many ways in which one can look at this, this early modern period, addressing

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:52.640
[Guest]: themes and processes and so on.

00:16:52.640 --> 00:16:59.960
[Guest]: And in the end, I found that I couldn't really leave Dara, partly because he's such a prominent

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:00.960
[Guest]: figure today.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:07.560
[Guest]: You know, I say in my introduction, that these Mughal royals, most of them emperors, but

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.720
[Guest]: some others also still live among us.

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:15.440
[Guest]: We feel we know them, we feel that they're just so familiar, you just need to call someone

00:17:15.440 --> 00:17:19.000
[Guest]: Aurangzeb, you know, in India, and you know that it's a slur, you know, it's something

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:24.480
[Guest]: like, you know, you're saying something really nasty about them, they're treacherous, they're

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:26.960
[Guest]: not loyal to their families, and so on.

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:34.080
[Guest]: But having looked at Mughal primary sources, I knew that the story was much more complicated

00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:35.080
[Guest]: than that.

00:17:35.080 --> 00:17:43.800
[Guest]: So I think if one dips one's feet in the water of the Persian sources of the time, sources

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:50.040
[Guest]: in other languages, you do get the sense that things are very different.

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:56.360
[Guest]: And then there's another kind of principle, a methodological principle of writing history

00:17:56.360 --> 00:18:03.240
[Guest]: that are used, which was to try to look at the sources that were contemporaneous with

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:08.680
[Guest]: Dara, or that if one looks at later sources to make sure that you know that, to make sure

00:18:08.680 --> 00:18:12.440
[Guest]: that you're sort of disclosing that these are later sources, these are written by people

00:18:12.440 --> 00:18:15.880
[Guest]: who are not eyewitnesses, who are not contemporaries.

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:20.960
[Guest]: And you know, they might have another axe to grind, they might have, there's definitely

00:18:20.960 --> 00:18:28.200
[Guest]: covered by either being written in Aurangzeb's time, or later with the benefit of hindsight.

00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:33.240
[Guest]: So that it definitely tells you a lot about the period in which those sources were written.

00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:38.720
[Guest]: But we want to know how Dara was representing himself, again, you know, once being quite

00:18:38.720 --> 00:18:43.880
[Guest]: careful about avoiding any, just any kernel of core historical truth, because what you

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:46.800
[Guest]: have is just a new way of representations.

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:51.480
[Guest]: And if we look at the representations from that period, what are they saying?

00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:53.320
[Guest]: What are they telling us?

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:57.720
[Guest]: So that's the question that I kept in mind when I was doing my research.

00:18:57.720 --> 00:19:00.200
[Amit Varma]: And what drew you to the project to begin with?

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:05.140
[Amit Varma]: Like you said, it's a very resonant story, the Dara versus Aurangzeb, it's almost a foundational

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:08.160
[Amit Varma]: story of Islam in the subcontinent in many senses.

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:10.960
[Amit Varma]: So were you sort of drawn into exploring that further?

00:19:10.960 --> 00:19:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Or during your readings, did you find that, wait a minute, this guy is much more complicated

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:20.120
[Amit Varma]: than all of this, and I need to dig into this deeper, like, which came first, you're choosing

00:19:20.120 --> 00:19:23.040
[Amit Varma]: the story or the story choosing you as it were?

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:30.120
[Guest]: So I think what came first was what I did during my doctoral studies, my PhD studies

00:19:30.120 --> 00:19:36.920
[Guest]: at Harvard, I wanted to study some aspect of the Sanskrit Persian encounter.

00:19:36.920 --> 00:19:40.160
[Guest]: And I found that I couldn't really avoid Dara Shukoh.

00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:42.920
[Guest]: He is such a central figure after Akbar.

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:48.600
[Guest]: I mean, he is a Mughal royal who's producing his own translations, with help of course

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:50.880
[Guest]: and collaboration.

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:55.960
[Guest]: And that I found that people were reading his writings later on.

00:19:55.960 --> 00:20:01.040
[Guest]: So he had this really long, diachronic influence.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:02.640
[Guest]: And he was such a key figure.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:08.880
[Guest]: So I started just looking at the works that he wrote, you know, I did a fresh translation

00:20:08.880 --> 00:20:13.200
[Guest]: of the Majnul Bahrain that I'm sitting on, I haven't published that yet.

00:20:13.200 --> 00:20:15.920
[Guest]: And I looked at his Surya Akbar and so on.

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:20.480
[Guest]: And then later on, when I wanted to write a book, I realized that I have to place this

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:22.880
[Guest]: in its social and political context.

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:28.440
[Guest]: So the book is, you know, it's quite, quite different from what I did during my, my PhD.

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:33.360
[Guest]: But my initial attraction was just to look at Dara Shukoh, you know, he was, he's just

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:39.640
[Guest]: this amazingly prolific figure, and to sort of to see, to look at his intellectual trajectory

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:44.560
[Guest]: to see, you know, how he was developing his thought and his ideas.

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:48.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, in a recent interview, which of course I linked from the show notes, you said

00:20:48.360 --> 00:20:52.200
[Amit Varma]: something I found very interesting, which is that the narrative task of a historian

00:20:52.200 --> 00:20:57.080
[Amit Varma]: is to make history complex again, which of course speaks to how in trying to make sense

00:20:57.080 --> 00:21:01.320
[Amit Varma]: of the world, we necessarily have to come up with simple narratives for everything.

00:21:01.320 --> 00:21:05.720
[Amit Varma]: And very often, when we look at history, these simple narratives are convenient, simple narratives

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:10.960
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that they bolster whatever our vision of the world is, in fact, you quoted

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:15.360
[Amit Varma]: Baths in your book, and you said that, you know, you invoked his saying history evaporates.

00:21:15.360 --> 00:21:20.400
[Amit Varma]: And you said that, in your words, quote, myth also clads ideological structures in a narrative

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:25.600
[Amit Varma]: form, stop quote, and obviously, there are very deeper entrenched narratives that are

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:26.600
[Amit Varma]: at play here.

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:32.080
[Amit Varma]: And now when you get into it, it's almost as if and you also chose a narrative form,

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:38.160
[Amit Varma]: which I suppose, in some senses was meant to reach out to a broader than academic readership.

00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:43.360
[Amit Varma]: So obviously, you want to also tell a compelling story, which you think is, you know, different

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:47.400
[Amit Varma]: from the simple narratives which previously exist.

00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:53.480
[Amit Varma]: But where do you maintain that balance of sort of being complex and being coherent?

00:21:53.480 --> 00:21:58.440
[Amit Varma]: Was that a challenge? And was it also a challenge that there is so little material to play with

00:21:58.440 --> 00:22:00.320
[Amit Varma]: that you're being forced to make choices?

00:22:00.320 --> 00:22:04.240
[Amit Varma]: And are those choices something that you're then examining why you're making those choices?

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:09.200
[Guest]: Yes, of course, you know, there are a lot of choices involved in one's telling of the

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:13.520
[Guest]: story, for instance, you know, so this is so this book, it is a narrative.

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:20.800
[Guest]: It's a retelling of the simple myth of Tara Shukla and Aurangzeb and as you know, as you

00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:26.200
[Guest]: mentioned, I'm calling this a myth, not because I'm saying it's not true, but because these

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:30.800
[Guest]: are stories that live with us, they live with us, there are ciphers and sort of short forms

00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:36.480
[Guest]: for a whole range of ideas and ideological positions.

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:41.640
[Guest]: So when I'm turning this into a story, I am making choices about what to include what

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:43.520
[Guest]: to say.

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:46.920
[Guest]: And I think that's something that happens no matter what kind of book you write.

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:51.040
[Guest]: One could write a more conventional academic sort of book, the kind of book that has an

00:22:51.040 --> 00:22:55.880
[Guest]: introduction with a chapter outline, and a conclusion sort of summing up these things

00:22:55.880 --> 00:23:00.120
[Guest]: and and, you know, perhaps some thematic chapters, and you're still making choices, you're making

00:23:00.120 --> 00:23:06.160
[Guest]: choices about, about what to include what fits in with your argument, what doesn't necessarily

00:23:06.160 --> 00:23:09.880
[Guest]: address your argument, what isn't so useful to you.

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:18.280
[Guest]: And in this case, I chose to present my argument in the form of a narrative, so doing more

00:23:18.280 --> 00:23:23.920
[Guest]: showing than telling, though, of course, there is definitely some telling that goes on.

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:29.560
[Guest]: But what this book isn't, it isn't a grab bag of every single fact in the world about

00:23:29.560 --> 00:23:30.560
[Guest]: Tara Shukla and Aurangzeb.

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:34.840
[Guest]: And that's partly because, you know, no publisher would really want to publish something like

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:35.840
[Guest]: that.

00:23:35.840 --> 00:23:39.960
[Guest]: There are word limits, there are, you know, all kinds of things that have to be negotiated.

00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:46.080
[Guest]: So if you want to book, you know, something between two covers that can reach a fairly

00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:51.800
[Guest]: wide audience, there are there are always choices that one needs.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And what were your sort of models in terms of books which attempted a similar thing a

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:02.280
[Amit Varma]: show don't tell approach with a distant period of history, you know, a very serious book

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:06.400
[Amit Varma]: written with a lot of rigor, but told in a narrative style that can, you know, appeal

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:07.480
[Amit Varma]: to larger audiences.

00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:11.840
[Amit Varma]: So who were the sort of writers of history who you admired and learned from?

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:13.880
[Guest]: So that's a great question.

00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:21.880
[Guest]: And I didn't have a whole lot of models from this period of South Asian history.

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:26.840
[Guest]: You know, loads of historians whom I admire, of course.

00:24:26.840 --> 00:24:31.480
[Guest]: But when I was writing this, you know, I didn't have a precise model.

00:24:31.480 --> 00:24:35.160
[Guest]: It's not as though this is a genre.

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:40.720
[Guest]: It so happened that as I was writing the book, and as it was in production, there was a whole

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:48.360
[Guest]: slew of of mobile biographies that that came out, some by academic colleagues, one or two,

00:24:48.360 --> 00:24:53.400
[Guest]: and a lot of them by other writers in South Asia, which I think is a is a wonderful trend.

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.600
[Guest]: There wasn't a whole lot, you know, I can just think of the top of my head of, you know,

00:24:57.600 --> 00:25:02.280
[Guest]: some, some writers whom I read, you know, there is the American historian Jim Lepore,

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:07.080
[Guest]: who writes very prolific essays for the New Yorker and also other books.

00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:16.760
[Guest]: And, again, she has this amazing gift for narrative history and kind of lucid prose.

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:23.440
[Guest]: So she's, she's one author whom I have been reading, you know, and I've also been really

00:25:23.440 --> 00:25:30.800
[Guest]: impressed by Shamsur Rehman Farooqui's sort of luxuriant novels that really bring to life

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:35.480
[Guest]: the times that they talk about, and there are all these intricate narrative threads

00:25:35.480 --> 00:25:37.280
[Guest]: and characters woven in.

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:40.560
[Guest]: So that, you know, was another sort of indirect influence.

00:25:40.560 --> 00:25:50.400
[Guest]: You know, I was drawing inspiration from novelists as much as from historians, except that, you

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:54.880
[Guest]: know, I was trying to piece together this narrative after being really steeped in the

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:56.440
[Guest]: primary sources of the era.

00:25:56.440 --> 00:26:01.440
[Guest]: So I had to construct something that I hoped would read a bit like a novel, except that

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:06.360
[Guest]: it was all nonfiction.

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:10.240
[Amit Varma]: In the introduction to your book, you sort of pointed out about how you were at first

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:15.240
[Amit Varma]: hesitant about writing it, because you didn't want to, you know, privilege this whole great

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:21.720
[Amit Varma]: men sort of way of history, and so much of the narrative around Dara is actually a great

00:26:21.720 --> 00:26:25.600
[Amit Varma]: man narrative that had he been emperor instead of Aurangzeb, the entire subcontinent would

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:28.000
[Amit Varma]: have proceeded in a different direction.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:31.480
[Amit Varma]: And this is something I kind of like to ask the historians who come on the show that,

00:26:31.480 --> 00:26:34.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, where do you stand in the great man theory of history?

00:26:34.040 --> 00:26:37.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I'd be interested in having you elaborate on that.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:38.000
[Guest]: Yes.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:42.880
[Guest]: So the thing about, you know, great men is that we tend to really love them in the present

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:44.520
[Guest]: moment.

00:26:44.520 --> 00:26:46.600
[Guest]: That's how we tend to look at history.

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:51.880
[Guest]: So in the popular imagination in South Asia, history is this succession of either great

00:26:51.880 --> 00:27:01.480
[Guest]: men or depraved men who, you know, had tremendous control over steering its course and so on.

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:07.320
[Guest]: So if you write about someone, it must mean that you sort of, you know, like greatly admire

00:27:07.320 --> 00:27:08.320
[Guest]: them.

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:13.000
[Guest]: And, you know, I do, I do have empathy for Dara Shukla, I feel that, you know, I've tried

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:16.280
[Guest]: to understand things from his perspective and there are lots of things I like about

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:21.720
[Guest]: him, but I would be very hesitant to elevate him or any Mughal emperor for that matter

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:25.640
[Guest]: to this great man status.

00:27:25.640 --> 00:27:30.240
[Guest]: So I'll just talk about my hesitancy for a bit, and then I'll go back to why I still

00:27:30.240 --> 00:27:32.640
[Guest]: think it's important to study these figures.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:41.080
[Guest]: I'm hesitant because the Mughal Empire was about a whole lot more than just the emperor

00:27:41.080 --> 00:27:42.080
[Guest]: and the court.

00:27:42.080 --> 00:27:46.600
[Guest]: It was a fairly loose-knit empire.

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:56.560
[Guest]: It was held together by a whole array of nobility, chieftains, and so on, who were really masters

00:27:56.560 --> 00:28:01.720
[Guest]: of their own domains.

00:28:01.720 --> 00:28:07.680
[Guest]: The emperor was still important as a figurehead and as an idea.

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:15.040
[Guest]: Dara Shukla, you know, lived during the period where the idea of the sacred sovereign was

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:24.280
[Guest]: really at its height, so yes, you know, the idea of this all-powerful emperor who is responsible

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:31.600
[Guest]: for keeping the whole, the empire in a state of harmony and balance was very important.

00:28:31.600 --> 00:28:38.760
[Guest]: And yet our obsession with great men can obscure us to broader facts of cultural process that

00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:45.080
[Guest]: exist quite separately, quite independent of the actions of emperors.

00:28:45.080 --> 00:28:50.800
[Guest]: There are a whole range of environmental changes, for instance, that are taking place that also

00:28:50.800 --> 00:28:57.840
[Guest]: have an impact on where people live, what religion they might choose, and so on.

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:03.280
[Guest]: Richard Eaton's work on Bengal is a case in point.

00:29:03.280 --> 00:29:07.000
[Guest]: So there are a whole range of other factors that are far more important than men.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:12.480
[Guest]: And of course, you know, there is the gender dimension that our focus on men has obscured

00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:15.960
[Guest]: the important role of women and others in history.

00:29:15.960 --> 00:29:21.520
[Guest]: But still, it's hard to get away from these figures because I think it's important to

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:26.040
[Guest]: study them in their complexity as well.

00:29:26.040 --> 00:29:30.040
[Guest]: And for Dara Shukoh, his influence ranges far beyond his time.

00:29:30.040 --> 00:29:36.520
[Guest]: In fact, my current work, which we can speak about in a bit, partly addresses how people

00:29:36.520 --> 00:29:46.280
[Guest]: were reading Dara Shukoh much after his death and how his own studies of Indic thought spawned

00:29:46.280 --> 00:29:54.080
[Guest]: all kinds of other intellectual debates, changes, and dialogues that he couldn't even have predicted.

00:29:54.080 --> 00:29:59.880
[Guest]: So if you're looking at the section of elite society in pre-modern and even in colonial

00:29:59.880 --> 00:30:04.720
[Guest]: India, the small section that was literate, or a larger section that was kind of literate

00:30:04.720 --> 00:30:09.960
[Guest]: aware, figures like Dara Shukoh do tend to have an important reach.

00:30:09.960 --> 00:30:14.640
[Guest]: And they also remind us that what happened at the court wasn't something that was just

00:30:14.640 --> 00:30:19.440
[Guest]: purely located in that context, that what happened at the court was informed by other

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:24.240
[Guest]: intellectual conversations, dialogues, cultural processes that were taking place outside the

00:30:24.240 --> 00:30:25.240
[Guest]: court.

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:31.880
[Guest]: So Dara Shukoh wasn't alone, it wasn't just that he invented inter-religious dialogue.

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:37.480
[Guest]: He was participating in something that took place in many other venues as well.

00:30:37.480 --> 00:30:41.560
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, one of the things that I have got a sense of in the past few months by reading

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:46.040
[Amit Varma]: books like yours and Ira Mukherjee's book, and she was also on the show a while back,

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:51.760
[Amit Varma]: and Mani Mukta Sharma and so on, is that, you know, we think of these as almost caricature

00:30:51.760 --> 00:30:57.040
[Amit Varma]: figures that Aurangzeb is this evil bigoted guy and Dara Shukoh is this tolerant secular

00:30:57.040 --> 00:30:58.040
[Amit Varma]: guy.

00:30:58.040 --> 00:31:01.920
[Amit Varma]: But actually, you know, the emperor wasn't the be-all and end-all of the empire, there

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:07.240
[Amit Varma]: was a deep state, there was a political economy in which the women of the harems were deeply

00:31:07.240 --> 00:31:08.240
[Amit Varma]: involved.

00:31:08.240 --> 00:31:12.840
[Amit Varma]: And also, as we'll discuss shortly, these binaries also don't hold true in the sense

00:31:12.840 --> 00:31:17.440
[Amit Varma]: that Aurangzeb was also to an extent steeped in culture and engaging with the world and

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:21.640
[Amit Varma]: if Dara Shukoh had come to power, he would probably have beheaded his brothers as well.

00:31:21.640 --> 00:31:26.800
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, it's not that things would have necessarily been as different as we try to

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:27.800
[Amit Varma]: make it.

00:31:27.800 --> 00:31:33.100
[Amit Varma]: I mean, my friend Ashok Malik once wrote a piece where he called, you know, the execution

00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:37.400
[Amit Varma]: of Dara Shukoh, the partition before partition, which you've sort of cited in your book, and

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:42.840
[Amit Varma]: I was, you know, which is almost emblematic of these definitive, simplistic takes that

00:31:42.840 --> 00:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: one draw of these.

00:31:43.840 --> 00:31:47.120
[Amit Varma]: And I was also, you know, struck by, and I'll quote this bit from your book, because it

00:31:47.120 --> 00:31:50.800
[Amit Varma]: overall seems to sum up how the binaries play out where you talk about the trial of Dara

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:55.080
[Amit Varma]: Shukoh and you write, quote, the trial is a powerful motif because it transforms a story

00:31:55.080 --> 00:31:58.960
[Amit Varma]: about 17th century India into a narrative about today.

00:31:58.960 --> 00:32:02.760
[Amit Varma]: It creates a dialectic between two opposing visions of Islam.

00:32:02.760 --> 00:32:06.520
[Amit Varma]: Islam is zealous extremism immediately familiar in our present context.

00:32:06.520 --> 00:32:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And it's counterpoint Islam as Sufi antinomianism.

00:32:09.560 --> 00:32:15.040
[Amit Varma]: But even without the supposed trial, the brothers clash is a story that addresses the deepest

00:32:15.040 --> 00:32:18.120
[Amit Varma]: questions of who we are and how we got here.

00:32:18.120 --> 00:32:19.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:22.280
[Amit Varma]: And you also relate in your book about how through history we look at these two very

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:28.080
[Amit Varma]: divergent views of say Aurangzeb and Dara Shukoh where Muhammad Iqbal and Rumuzi Bekhudi

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:34.040
[Amit Varma]: praises Aurangzeb as, you know, that ascetic, that sword master and all of that.

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:37.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Ashok Malik calls it the partition before partition.

00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:41.280
[Amit Varma]: But equally on the other side, you have, you know, the two 20th century bios of Dara that

00:32:41.280 --> 00:32:45.520
[Amit Varma]: you've referred to by Kalik Ranjan Kanungo and Vikramjeet Hasrat, where both of them

00:32:45.520 --> 00:32:46.760
[Amit Varma]: praise him.

00:32:46.760 --> 00:32:51.440
[Amit Varma]: And Kanungo says the world has not become richer in any way by the long reign of Aurangzeb,

00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:54.920
[Amit Varma]: but it would certainly have been poorer without Dara Shukoh.

00:32:54.920 --> 00:32:55.920
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:32:55.920 --> 00:32:59.640
[Amit Varma]: And one, of course, we'll talk about how these binaries aren't true.

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:04.120
[Amit Varma]: But the question that struck me while I was reading these is that at some point in our

00:33:04.120 --> 00:33:08.440
[Amit Varma]: history, what is happening, and I think it happened repeatedly over the late 19th century

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:13.780
[Amit Varma]: and the early 20th century, is that these conflicting ideas of Islam are competing with

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:16.140
[Amit Varma]: the conflicting ideas of India.

00:33:16.140 --> 00:33:21.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, as in, where does a lot of the debates that were playing out, you know, where does

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:25.780
[Amit Varma]: the good Muslim stand with relation to his fealty towards India?

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:31.360
[Amit Varma]: This was part of the reason why, for example, you know, Mahatma Gandhi's alliance with the

00:33:31.360 --> 00:33:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Ali brothers at the time of the Khilafat movement seems so discordant, because, you know, while

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:41.240
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi is fighting for a vision of India as a nation state, per se, the Ali brothers are

00:33:41.240 --> 00:33:47.200
[Amit Varma]: fighting for a larger Ummah where your allegiance is to somewhere else entirely.

00:33:47.200 --> 00:33:52.760
[Amit Varma]: So what are sort of your thoughts also on how these competing ideas of Islam have played

00:33:52.760 --> 00:33:56.400
[Amit Varma]: out against the competing ideas of India?

00:33:56.400 --> 00:34:00.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I realize this is a sort of a larger question than, you know, what your book is

00:34:00.160 --> 00:34:01.160
[Amit Varma]: about.

00:34:01.160 --> 00:34:05.640
[Amit Varma]: But because that's, of course, set in those Mughal times, but I'd love to know what thoughts

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:06.640
[Guest]: you've had on these.

00:34:06.640 --> 00:34:07.640
[Guest]: Sure.

00:34:07.640 --> 00:34:08.640
[Guest]: So thank you.

00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:12.680
[Guest]: So, you know, of course, the Khilafat movement is very, very modern.

00:34:12.680 --> 00:34:18.560
[Guest]: It comes at a time when ideas of Islam are changing.

00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:24.880
[Guest]: And there is this kind of political Islam that is forming in opposition to colonialism.

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:31.520
[Guest]: You know, there is a Muslim public sphere, there's a Hindu public sphere.

00:34:31.520 --> 00:34:39.840
[Guest]: So colonialism played an important role in transforming how these communities drew boundaries

00:34:39.840 --> 00:34:44.080
[Guest]: around their identities, how they saw each other, how they saw their role.

00:34:44.080 --> 00:34:50.920
[Guest]: In the case of Dara Shukoh, yes, it's depending on which side of the border you're on or what

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:58.160
[Guest]: ideology you gravitate towards, you know, Dara Shukoh is either this terrible heretic,

00:34:58.160 --> 00:35:02.400
[Guest]: you know, it was like just as well that Aurangzeb got him out of the way.

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:08.520
[Guest]: You see this in a lot of narratives from Pakistan, not all, but at all, you know, not kind of

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:18.200
[Guest]: more state-sponsored narratives, or Dara Shukoh is this wonderful philosopher and gentle mystic

00:35:18.200 --> 00:35:20.200
[Guest]: who really ought to have been ruler.

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:24.400
[Guest]: But there's always a caveat, there's always a little bit of doubt with that, because even

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:29.720
[Guest]: those, like his wonderful earlier 20th century biographers, Phanungo and Hester, even those

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:36.080
[Guest]: who praise him, they still feel, well, you know, he was, yes, he had these amazing views

00:35:36.080 --> 00:35:42.800
[Guest]: and was interested in Sanskrit and Indic thought, but there was actually no way he could really

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:44.120
[Guest]: practically rule.

00:35:44.120 --> 00:35:50.520
[Guest]: He was too weak, he was uninterested in the throne, and you really needed someone more

00:35:50.520 --> 00:35:52.720
[Guest]: ruthless like Aurangzeb.

00:35:52.720 --> 00:35:58.800
[Guest]: So it was inevitable that somebody who was more crafty, who was more capable of being

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:00.160
[Amit Varma]: the emperor.

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:05.200
[Amit Varma]: And this, as you've pointed out, is not the truth, obviously, I mean, that whole binary

00:36:05.200 --> 00:36:09.440
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, Dara had his head in the clouds, and he was just doing all these religious

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:14.160
[Amit Varma]: studies and meeting Sufi saints, and Aurangzeb was the guy who was going out and, you know,

00:36:14.160 --> 00:36:16.480
[Amit Varma]: conquering territories and all that isn't true at all.

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:22.280
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Dara was Shah Jahan's chosen successor, in a sense, and they almost co-ruled

00:36:22.280 --> 00:36:23.560
[Amit Varma]: for many, many years.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:28.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, when people asked that hypothetical question of what would Dara have been as a

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.840
[Amit Varma]: ruler, what you've pointed out is that we already kind of know.

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:32.840
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely.

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:38.280
[Guest]: So, you know, one thing that I've tried to do is to disturb the idea that that's a very

00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:44.400
[Guest]: modern idea, that a ruler should not be interested in philosophy, that a ruler should, you know,

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:51.200
[Guest]: is not really the kind of person to have dialogues with ascetics, that belongs to a totally different

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:57.840
[Guest]: realm of life, and it's not part of an emperor or would-be emperor's political relations.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:01.840
[Guest]: And I've tried to show how Dara wasn't an outlier in this regard, he was actually following

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:04.400
[Guest]: an established Mughal tradition.

00:37:04.400 --> 00:37:08.480
[Guest]: He was, without acknowledging them, following in the footsteps of his great-grandfather

00:37:08.480 --> 00:37:16.400
[Guest]: Akbar and, to an extent as well, his own grandfather Jahangir, that he complemented his own father

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:21.960
[Guest]: Shah Jahan, who was often viewed as somebody who was more orthodox, he was paving the way

00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:28.080
[Guest]: for Aurangzeb's far, you know, stricter, more ascetic orthodox rule.

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:34.480
[Guest]: But Dara and Shah Jahan together were hosting Sanskrit pundits at the court who composed

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:41.280
[Guest]: poems in praise of them, you know, he was hosting all these intellectual and spiritual

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:45.840
[Guest]: dialogues and was very, very much part of what he was doing as a ruler, he certainly

00:37:45.840 --> 00:37:47.400
[Guest]: saw himself as one.

00:37:47.400 --> 00:37:53.040
[Guest]: Now Aurangzeb did have an advantage, Aurangzeb had the advantage of gaining a lot of military

00:37:53.040 --> 00:38:01.800
[Guest]: experience on his own, often in the face of, you know, either opposition and really irritating

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:04.880
[Guest]: micromanaging on the part of Shah Jahan.

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:12.600
[Guest]: He was able to govern the Deccan as well on his own, so he got a lot of independent experience

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:17.440
[Guest]: that served him well in the struggle for the throne later on.

00:38:17.440 --> 00:38:23.200
[Guest]: But it doesn't mean that, you know, Dara Shukrawal didn't prove himself as a future

00:38:23.200 --> 00:38:24.200
[Amit Varma]: emperor.

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:28.840
[Amit Varma]: No, I was, in fact, you mentioned micromanaging and there are these very funny bits in your

00:38:28.840 --> 00:38:33.120
[Amit Varma]: book, which are again, perfect examples of show don't tell and I love the bit about the

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:37.640
[Amit Varma]: mangoes where, you know, Aurangzeb I think is in Aurangabad and he's got to send and

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:41.440
[Amit Varma]: his dad is waiting for mangoes because it's Aurangzeb's duty to send him the mangoes as

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:43.600
[Amit Varma]: soon as the first good ones come.

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:47.480
[Amit Varma]: So Shah Jahan writes him a letter and says, have people stand below the tree, I can't

00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:50.360
[Amit Varma]: wait as soon as they come, they got to catch them as they fall.

00:38:50.360 --> 00:38:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Aurangzeb sends him mangoes and Shah Jahan replies that these are shitty mangoes and

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:59.600
[Amit Varma]: have you eaten my good mangoes and Aurangzeb has to reply that no, your highness, I would

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:01.000
[Amit Varma]: not dare to eat.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:06.160
[Amit Varma]: And of course, there's a more consequential version of this during the Kandahar battle

00:39:06.160 --> 00:39:11.040
[Amit Varma]: where you point out about how they are laying siege to Kandahar, which the Safaites have

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:16.200
[Amit Varma]: taken over and Aurangzeb who is on the ground who can see the conditions realizes that the

00:39:16.200 --> 00:39:20.440
[Amit Varma]: artillery is useless and he's in line with the suggestion that let's just attack from

00:39:20.440 --> 00:39:22.560
[Amit Varma]: one point and focus there.

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:27.220
[Amit Varma]: And he tells his dad and Papa Shah Jahan, you know, doing central planning from hundreds

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:31.720
[Amit Varma]: of miles away says no, no, we, you know, use those cannons and we'll, you know, attack

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:36.300
[Amit Varma]: from two places and he seems like such an, you know, must be such an irritating dad to

00:39:36.300 --> 00:39:40.000
[Amit Varma]: have to deal with for Aurangzeb, you know.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.720
[Amit Varma]: And since we're talking about sort of Shah Jahan, I found a really interesting character

00:39:44.720 --> 00:39:49.280
[Amit Varma]: because there are just so many sides to his persona that you can really paint him as anything

00:39:49.280 --> 00:39:55.320
[Amit Varma]: like you've pointed out, you know, his journey to the throne, of course, is incredibly bloody

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:58.800
[Amit Varma]: where he has to get rid of all his brothers and nephews and all of that.

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:03.040
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, you have the softer, more sensuous side of him, partly reflected, of

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:07.880
[Amit Varma]: course, in his deep love for his wife and, you know, the good deeds that he does.

00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:13.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, you point out an example of what, you know, today, I'm sure many people would jump

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:20.480
[Amit Varma]: on where in 1633, he decides to get a bunch of temples raised, including 66 under construction

00:40:20.480 --> 00:40:22.320
[Amit Varma]: temples in Banaras.

00:40:22.320 --> 00:40:26.680
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, later in the story, when Dara Shikoh is, you know, involving himself

00:40:26.680 --> 00:40:30.920
[Amit Varma]: with Indic philosophy, calling all these scholars to the court, it is Shah Jahan who is, as

00:40:30.920 --> 00:40:34.640
[Amit Varma]: you point out, giving them generous gifts and all of that.

00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:40.480
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, all these figures are so deeply complex and Shah Jahan himself is so complex.

00:40:40.480 --> 00:40:44.840
[Amit Varma]: This is a dude who, you know, did away with his whole damn family.

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:46.720
[Amit Varma]: And yet you see this side of him as well.

00:40:46.720 --> 00:40:52.200
[Amit Varma]: And in the end, you almost feel sorry for him because he's sort of imprisoned by Aurangzeb.

00:40:52.200 --> 00:40:57.440
[Amit Varma]: And one story that you pointed out is that, you know, after Dara Shikoh is killed, his

00:40:57.440 --> 00:41:01.360
[Amit Varma]: head is sent to Aurangzeb and there is, you know, so and this is another thing, there

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:02.800
[Amit Varma]: are so many versions of that story.

00:41:02.800 --> 00:41:06.440
[Amit Varma]: One version of the head story is that Dara Shikoh is beheaded and the head is brought

00:41:06.440 --> 00:41:08.640
[Amit Varma]: to Aurangzeb and he says, I don't want to look at it.

00:41:08.640 --> 00:41:13.440
[Amit Varma]: And the other version is that he stabs her three times, you know, and sends it to his

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:15.080
[Amit Varma]: dad.

00:41:15.080 --> 00:41:20.000
[Amit Varma]: So when you're reading all this delightfully juicy stuff, you know, and you have no way

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:21.680
[Amit Varma]: of knowing which one is true, right?

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:23.400
[Amit Varma]: So how do you navigate that?

00:41:23.400 --> 00:41:29.280
[Guest]: So with the head story, some of it, you can see if it falls into recognizable motifs and

00:41:29.280 --> 00:41:32.160
[Guest]: tropes that are used elsewhere.

00:41:32.160 --> 00:41:39.880
[Guest]: So you know, it's one of the head stories we told by the Italian adventurer Manucci.

00:41:39.880 --> 00:41:46.220
[Guest]: You see that what he's doing here is really making Dara Shikoh into a Christ-like figure.

00:41:46.220 --> 00:41:52.680
[Guest]: So whether or not the story is true, the way in which Manucci is recounting it serves a

00:41:52.680 --> 00:41:58.720
[Guest]: certain narrative end and definitely elicits horror and sympathy.

00:41:58.720 --> 00:42:05.880
[Guest]: And these are for things that the European travelers to India wanted to elicit in their

00:42:05.880 --> 00:42:06.880
[Guest]: readers.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:11.480
[Guest]: They spun all kinds of stories and we can't dismiss them completely, but their accounts

00:42:11.480 --> 00:42:20.960
[Guest]: are colored by the fact that they were transforming their adventures in India into entertainment

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:25.560
[Guest]: for the consumption of the European reading public.

00:42:25.560 --> 00:42:32.120
[Guest]: So they were fitting them into morals that were also familiar to their readers in the

00:42:32.120 --> 00:42:33.120
[Amit Varma]: world.

00:42:33.120 --> 00:42:34.120
[Amit Varma]: Right.

