[Amit Varma]: the book that before his intellectual journey really took off, like the sense that I got

00:45:18.520 --> 00:45:23.840
[Amit Varma]: initially, although this changes is that it was more of a spiritual journey than an intellectual

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:24.840
[Amit Varma]: journey.

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:31.520
[Amit Varma]: For example, you know, the way that he meets Mian Mir, for example, and almost instinctively,

00:45:31.520 --> 00:45:36.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, sort of prostrates himself before him and offers himself as a disciple.

00:45:36.840 --> 00:45:41.520
[Amit Varma]: And it just seems sort of very impulsive and even irrational, because it's not as if he's

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:45.280
[Amit Varma]: read like five books by this guy, and he, you know, really believes in his worldview

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:46.280
[Amit Varma]: and all that.

00:45:46.280 --> 00:45:51.160
[Amit Varma]: It's just that he's following some kind of an instinct to attain some kind of spiritual

00:45:51.160 --> 00:45:52.160
[Amit Varma]: growth.

00:45:52.160 --> 00:45:57.280
[Amit Varma]: And for much of that early period, like after Mian Mir dies, we see this, you know, you

00:45:57.280 --> 00:45:58.880
[Amit Varma]: talk about the visions he's having.

00:45:58.880 --> 00:46:04.080
[Amit Varma]: And this seemed like very sort of, I mean, I didn't know what to make of that because

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:09.480
[Amit Varma]: he's having visions where his former teacher comes to him in a dream, there is one vision

00:46:09.480 --> 00:46:15.600
[Amit Varma]: where his former teacher sort of unbuttons a shirt and then grabs him and there's this

00:46:15.600 --> 00:46:20.400
[Amit Varma]: nipple to nipple contact and it's almost like his heart has, you know, this whole sort of

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:25.800
[Amit Varma]: mystical exchange of the spirit happens, there are other visions where the Prophet Muhammad

00:46:25.800 --> 00:46:29.760
[Amit Varma]: comes to him in a vision, you know, and if this sort of stuff was to happen in modern

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:35.040
[Amit Varma]: times, you'd really sort of question whether this person needed help, right?

00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:37.200
[Amit Varma]: And but he's a prince and this stuff is happening.

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:40.880
[Amit Varma]: And later, of course, and it seems to me that the whole intellectual exploration where he

00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:46.520
[Amit Varma]: writes his book about the lives of the 400 Sufi saints and all that, that comes later.

00:46:46.520 --> 00:46:51.960
[Amit Varma]: So is that sort of a misreading on my part, or you know, that the narrative gave me that

00:46:51.960 --> 00:46:56.600
[Amit Varma]: impression and what do you make of that early, young questing Dara Shikoh who's doing all

00:46:56.600 --> 00:47:00.960
[Amit Varma]: these things like he literally prostrates himself first before Mian Mir and then when

00:47:00.960 --> 00:47:07.000
[Amit Varma]: he goes to Kashmir, you know, Mullah Shah, where he's doing things that no prince should

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:08.160
[Amit Varma]: really be doing.

00:47:08.160 --> 00:47:12.600
[Amit Varma]: But and at that point, you know, you just wonder that these are just religious godmen

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:17.360
[Amit Varma]: at that moment to him, he doesn't know any of them intimately yet, you can develop respect

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:21.560
[Amit Varma]: later once you get to know them, but he's just falling at their feet and offering himself

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:22.560
[Amit Varma]: as a disciple.

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:24.600
[Guest]: So what did you make of all that?

00:47:24.600 --> 00:47:25.600
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:31.400
[Guest]: I mean, of course, we live in a time where, you know, from a certain rational perspective,

00:47:31.400 --> 00:47:35.400
[Guest]: you know, all of this seems kind of strange and weird.

00:47:35.400 --> 00:47:41.000
[Guest]: But if you look at even our own times, we find that there is, especially today, the

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:46.040
[Guest]: political, spiritual, intellectual are actually really deeply enmeshed.

00:47:46.040 --> 00:47:51.280
[Guest]: And that was the case in Dara Shikoh's time, that it's, you know, hard to separate the

00:47:51.280 --> 00:47:56.520
[Guest]: political, for instance, from the spiritual, you know, Tip Akbar, who made these great

00:47:56.520 --> 00:48:02.400
[Guest]: public shows of piety, he would walk barefoot to the shrine of Monyuddin Chishti to pray

00:48:02.400 --> 00:48:07.600
[Guest]: for a son, you know, he would give thanks, and so on.

00:48:07.600 --> 00:48:14.720
[Guest]: So Dara Shikoh's displays of piety, that he was later telegraphing, not because he wasn't

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:18.920
[Guest]: an emperor, he didn't have an Abul Fazl, but you know, through his own writings, you know,

00:48:18.920 --> 00:48:25.360
[Guest]: I would say these are not merely kind of the rantings of a naive mystical prince with his

00:48:25.360 --> 00:48:27.080
[Guest]: head in the clouds.

00:48:27.080 --> 00:48:30.000
[Guest]: He was always making a particular argument.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:35.560
[Guest]: So for instance, when he talks about his first meeting with, with Mian Mir, and he meets

00:48:35.560 --> 00:48:39.960
[Guest]: Mian Mir, his father is actually the one who takes him, so his father, and then later we

00:48:39.960 --> 00:48:46.020
[Guest]: learn that even Jahangir had reverence for Mian Mir, so he's an established Sufi figure,

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:50.280
[Guest]: you can see that he has influence, because you know, emperors themselves are going giving

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:51.800
[Guest]: him respect.

00:48:51.800 --> 00:49:01.760
[Guest]: So he then shows how he had this amazing experience with him, he gets healed, and he shows Mian

00:49:01.760 --> 00:49:04.640
[Guest]: Mir true reverence and piety.

00:49:04.640 --> 00:49:09.360
[Guest]: And then he makes these kind of little nasty, sort of passive aggressive digs at his own

00:49:09.360 --> 00:49:14.400
[Guest]: father and his grandfather saying, yes, you know, and when they went to visit Mian Mir,

00:49:14.400 --> 00:49:19.640
[Guest]: they said they wanted to talk about spiritual matters and even sort of like, you know, confided

00:49:19.640 --> 00:49:25.480
[Guest]: that we're so sick of rulership, we just want to be like you and, you know, be a recluse

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:28.480
[Guest]: like you and then Mian Mir sharply rebuked them.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:33.480
[Guest]: So in this case, Dara Shukoh is showing himself in a good light, he's showing himself as the

00:49:33.480 --> 00:49:40.200
[Guest]: true Sufi murid, he's a true kind of follower of the path of Sufism, unlike other emperors.

00:49:40.200 --> 00:49:45.000
[Guest]: And then maybe this means that he has a special spiritual quality that other rulers don't

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:47.480
[Guest]: have, that he's destined for something really great.

00:49:47.480 --> 00:49:51.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the reason I found this striking, because I don't mean this as a criticism of

00:49:51.640 --> 00:49:55.320
[Amit Varma]: Dara Shukoh to say, Oh, look at that mad guy, he was having visions, I'm sorry, if it came

00:49:55.320 --> 00:49:56.320
[Amit Varma]: across that way.

00:49:56.320 --> 00:49:57.320
[Amit Varma]: That's not what I meant.

00:49:57.320 --> 00:50:03.160
[Amit Varma]: The why I found these incidences fascinating is that I was trying to, during the book,

00:50:03.160 --> 00:50:07.000
[Amit Varma]: and there are times where I felt I got glimpses of this, but I was trying to get a sense of

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:10.760
[Amit Varma]: what is his interior life, you know, Dara Shukoh's, what's the stuff that what does

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:15.720
[Amit Varma]: he want, you know, what's the stuff that causes turmoil in him, for example, when he does

00:50:15.720 --> 00:50:20.200
[Amit Varma]: all of this, like you pointed out, he's trying to portray a side of himself, is he posturing

00:50:20.200 --> 00:50:21.200
[Amit Varma]: for others?

00:50:21.200 --> 00:50:23.160
[Amit Varma]: Is he posturing for himself?

00:50:23.160 --> 00:50:27.080
[Amit Varma]: Is there sometimes an element of self delusion to that?

00:50:27.080 --> 00:50:31.600
[Amit Varma]: And does all of this, even if let's say he begins to act in a particular way, because

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:37.360
[Amit Varma]: he's posturing for others or for himself, does it then shape what he actually becomes?

00:50:37.360 --> 00:50:42.480
[Amit Varma]: Because later on, you know, he's written all these phenomenal books of scholarship, there's

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:47.800
[Amit Varma]: no question that his intellectual engagement with, you know, both Sufism and Islam and

00:50:47.800 --> 00:50:52.480
[Amit Varma]: later on the Indic religions at a much later stage was very deep and genuine.

00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:58.120
[Amit Varma]: But in this early stage, what I sometimes get a sense of this young person who is floundering

00:50:58.120 --> 00:51:03.280
[Amit Varma]: around for an identity and to define his place in the in the bigger scheme, is that a sense

00:51:03.280 --> 00:51:04.280
[Amit Varma]: you got?

00:51:04.280 --> 00:51:07.160
[Amit Varma]: And you've obviously read all his original stuff in the original Persian, right?

00:51:07.160 --> 00:51:10.280
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, do you get a sense of who is this person?

00:51:10.280 --> 00:51:11.280
[Amit Varma]: What does he want?

00:51:11.280 --> 00:51:14.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, strip away all the history and he's an emperor and all of that.

00:51:14.080 --> 00:51:15.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:51:15.080 --> 00:51:20.200
[Guest]: So, you know, that that raises a lot of interesting questions about how one reads these texts,

00:51:20.200 --> 00:51:24.720
[Guest]: how one looks at narratives of the self, this is, you know, we have, we have a very modern

00:51:24.720 --> 00:51:26.840
[Guest]: post enlightenment view of the self.

00:51:26.840 --> 00:51:29.400
[Guest]: The self is this autonomous being.

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:35.160
[Guest]: We have, you know, our own narratives of inner transformations, conversions, understandings

00:51:35.160 --> 00:51:36.160
[Guest]: and so on.

00:51:36.160 --> 00:51:41.480
[Guest]: We have now that we use the terms of modern psychotherapy, psychoanalysis to, you know,

00:51:41.480 --> 00:51:44.120
[Guest]: to talk about the self.

00:51:44.120 --> 00:51:48.640
[Guest]: And there were other ideas that and other concepts that people used to understand the

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:51.240
[Guest]: self in Dara Shukla's time.

00:51:51.240 --> 00:51:59.360
[Guest]: So it's hard to make a distinction between public performance and the inner journey of

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:00.920
[Guest]: the self.

00:52:00.920 --> 00:52:05.440
[Guest]: It's very hard to make that distinction because it's not one that Dara Shukla makes, you know,

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:10.560
[Guest]: it's not as though we have a private diary where he's giving us his private outpourings

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:16.040
[Guest]: and then he has another, you know, some other documents that talk about his, his public

00:52:16.040 --> 00:52:17.040
[Guest]: persona.

00:52:17.040 --> 00:52:22.200
[Guest]: But I think we can definitely see a journey and a trajectory when Dara Shukla plunges

00:52:22.200 --> 00:52:28.520
[Guest]: into spiritual affairs, again, it's, it's not merely kind of cold and instrumental that

00:52:28.520 --> 00:52:33.240
[Guest]: he's like just going and paying respects to some, you know, Sufi because he has to, because

00:52:33.240 --> 00:52:34.920
[Guest]: it's part of his duty.

00:52:34.920 --> 00:52:40.600
[Guest]: He is actually working on cultivating and transforming the self.

00:52:40.600 --> 00:52:46.900
[Guest]: And this has been a preoccupation in India in many, many contexts, whether one sees this

00:52:46.900 --> 00:52:52.080
[Guest]: in the concept of the Rajarshi, you know, the kind of, again, the ruler who is also

00:52:52.080 --> 00:52:53.080
[Guest]: an ascetic.

00:52:53.080 --> 00:52:59.080
[Guest]: So we have lots of other, lots of examples, we have lots of examples of, you know, sages,

00:52:59.080 --> 00:53:05.160
[Guest]: ascetics, renunciants from different religious traditions who, who would work on this.

00:53:05.160 --> 00:53:11.720
[Guest]: And we have a whole tradition of rulers who either renounced the throne or stayed on the

00:53:11.720 --> 00:53:14.740
[Guest]: throne and engaged in asceticism.

00:53:14.740 --> 00:53:20.840
[Guest]: So it's, it's not surprising that later on, one of the models for Dara Shukla is Ram,

00:53:20.840 --> 00:53:27.440
[Guest]: not the Ram necessarily of the Ramayan, you know, who is in exile and then becomes a ruler

00:53:27.440 --> 00:53:28.440
[Guest]: of Ayodhya.

00:53:28.440 --> 00:53:36.200
[Guest]: But this is the Ram of the Yoga Vasishta, where Ram is a young prince and his guru Vasishta

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:42.800
[Guest]: takes him on the spiritual journey by telling him a whole range of interlocking stories.

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:47.760
[Guest]: One story leads to the other story, and Ram is reaching different levels of spiritual

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:52.400
[Guest]: perfection, finally, until he reaches Jivanmukti.

00:53:52.400 --> 00:53:57.880
[Guest]: And it's this idea of Jivanmukti was one that was very attractive to Mughal emperors, you

00:53:57.880 --> 00:54:04.160
[Guest]: know, Jahangir had beautifully lavishly illustrated manuscripts of the Yoga Vasishta, there was

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:08.400
[Guest]: one that was translated for Akbar, you know, Jahangir had a special one translated.

00:54:08.400 --> 00:54:12.200
[Guest]: Dara Shukla was also very interested in this text, and even though all the others had their

00:54:12.200 --> 00:54:14.840
[Guest]: own versions, he also got his own version of it.

00:54:14.840 --> 00:54:20.480
[Guest]: And it was a text that, in different abridgments, circulated all around South Asia.

00:54:20.480 --> 00:54:26.480
[Guest]: And even today, you know, whether it's the Yoga Vasishta, or whether it's a similar Vedic

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:30.800
[Guest]: text on liberation, you find them everywhere, they're very popular, circulated by Gita Press,

00:54:30.800 --> 00:54:33.040
[Guest]: they're found in railway stations, and so on.

00:54:33.040 --> 00:54:38.360
[Guest]: So it's an idea of enduring satisfaction, because at this point, this was a way in which

00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:44.640
[Guest]: a king or a ruler could be liberated, and then he could still carry out his royal tasks.

00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:47.240
[Guest]: So, you know, what could be better than that?

00:54:47.240 --> 00:54:53.720
[Guest]: And then later on, these ideas became very important for merchants, especially for those

00:54:53.720 --> 00:55:02.000
[Guest]: of the middle castes, you know, so they weren't necessarily going and kind of being ascetics,

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:07.480
[Guest]: they were engaged in earning money, they were engaged in the material world.

00:55:07.480 --> 00:55:11.960
[Guest]: And at the same time, they cultivated a great sense of asceticism, you know, we see that

00:55:11.960 --> 00:55:16.760
[Guest]: with certain version of business families, you know, there's a great emphasis on personal

00:55:16.760 --> 00:55:23.240
[Guest]: asceticism, as well as amassing a lot of material wealth in the world.

00:55:23.240 --> 00:55:29.600
[Guest]: And so how do you balance that, you know, the Yoga Vasishta is a good guide for that,

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:32.080
[Amit Varma]: which Ganesh also found quite useful.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:36.120
[Amit Varma]: So would it be fair to say, and I'm just thinking aloud that then there are two sort of dual

00:55:36.120 --> 00:55:38.200
[Amit Varma]: imperatives that seem to come into play.

00:55:38.200 --> 00:55:43.460
[Amit Varma]: And one is that you are an emperor, and you have conquered all the lands you can conquer,

00:55:43.460 --> 00:55:44.640
[Amit Varma]: but you cannot conquer death.

00:55:44.640 --> 00:55:45.640
[Amit Varma]: So what do we do?

00:55:45.640 --> 00:55:47.040
[Amit Varma]: And that sort of leads to this quest.

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:50.600
[Amit Varma]: But the other side of that is that, actually, you've conquered nothing, because you've got

00:55:50.600 --> 00:55:55.040
[Amit Varma]: relatives plotting against you, and every moment is stressful in some way or the other.

00:55:55.040 --> 00:55:56.680
[Amit Varma]: And you got to watch your back.

00:55:56.680 --> 00:55:59.120
[Amit Varma]: And this stuff gives you some release.

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:01.400
[Amit Varma]: So you know, would both of these be factors, you think?

00:56:01.400 --> 00:56:03.400
[Guest]: Yes, you know, I definitely agree.

00:56:03.400 --> 00:56:11.440
[Guest]: I mean, Dara Shukoh, he certainly was going far deeper down this route than a lot of other

00:56:11.440 --> 00:56:12.440
[Guest]: Mughals.

00:56:12.440 --> 00:56:16.840
[Guest]: Again, you know, but he wasn't unique, you know, his brother Murad had a Sufi peer, and

00:56:16.840 --> 00:56:20.680
[Guest]: he was always in contact with him, and the peer was always giving him guidance.

00:56:20.680 --> 00:56:24.640
[Guest]: Aurangzeb met a whole range of peers, Aurangzeb was more savvy in that way, you know, he didn't

00:56:24.640 --> 00:56:26.680
[Guest]: put all his eggs in one basket.

00:56:26.680 --> 00:56:32.640
[Guest]: But Shuja also paid reverence to Mullah Shah, the Sufi peer of Shah Jahan's household, and

00:56:32.640 --> 00:56:33.640
[Guest]: especially Dara Shukoh.

00:56:33.640 --> 00:56:40.280
[Guest]: So there were ways in which all the others were doing this, but Dara more than the others

00:56:40.280 --> 00:56:45.600
[Guest]: was really cultivating himself as the quintessential philosopher, you know.

00:56:45.600 --> 00:56:49.760
[Amit Varma]: It's also interesting how in the book, you talk about the influence on the Mughal kings

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:55.520
[Amit Varma]: of the example of Alexander, like you point out how Jahangir in one of his books quotes

00:56:55.520 --> 00:57:00.640
[Amit Varma]: this following line, quote, sovereignty brooks no bonds between fathers and sons and emperor

00:57:00.640 --> 00:57:06.040
[Amit Varma]: has no relatives, stock quote, which you point out is from the Iskandar Nama by Nizami Ganjavi,

00:57:06.040 --> 00:57:08.520
[Amit Varma]: which is, again, about Alexander.

00:57:08.520 --> 00:57:13.320
[Amit Varma]: And there are these two sides to Alexander, both of which seem very relevant to Dara Shukoh.

00:57:13.320 --> 00:57:17.800
[Amit Varma]: One is, of course, that you have no friends, and you got to watch out for your brothers.

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:23.560
[Amit Varma]: And as we've seen in Shah Jahan and Jahangir and earlier that, and in, of course, poor

00:57:23.560 --> 00:57:27.440
[Amit Varma]: Dara Shukoh's own generation that you basically have to get rid of all your brothers and nephews

00:57:27.440 --> 00:57:29.840
[Amit Varma]: or at the very least blind them.

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:34.240
[Amit Varma]: So that's one angle where he's growing up, he is the chosen one of the emperor.

00:57:34.240 --> 00:57:37.280
[Amit Varma]: But he's got an eye, he's the eldest son, but there's no primogenitor.

00:57:37.280 --> 00:57:40.520
[Amit Varma]: So it isn't that, you know, the eldest son automatically becomes king.

00:57:40.520 --> 00:57:42.400
[Amit Varma]: So he's got an eye on the prize.

00:57:42.400 --> 00:57:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you've pointed out how in the book, he'll try to influence things his father

00:57:46.200 --> 00:57:50.480
[Amit Varma]: does about, you know, sending Aurangzeb somewhere or, you know, making sure that two of the

00:57:50.480 --> 00:57:55.120
[Amit Varma]: other brothers don't meet so they can't plot with each other and all of that.

00:57:55.120 --> 00:57:59.880
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, there is that very realpolitik kind of, you know, eye on the throne, watch

00:57:59.880 --> 00:58:02.320
[Amit Varma]: out for everyone and beware of your brothers.

00:58:02.320 --> 00:58:05.680
[Amit Varma]: And on the other side, there is that intellectual and spiritual quest.

00:58:05.680 --> 00:58:10.400
[Amit Varma]: And Alexander, of course, also famously was on his own kind of intellectual quest.

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:14.840
[Amit Varma]: And you also see that mirroring itself out, you know, very often on a tangent, it's very

00:58:14.840 --> 00:58:19.320
[Amit Varma]: hard for me to imagine those times, because how do people gain the knowledge of the world?

00:58:19.320 --> 00:58:22.360
[Amit Varma]: There are no books, there's no television, there's no internet, there's nothing.

00:58:22.360 --> 00:58:26.080
[Amit Varma]: And yet you have these heroes like Alexander and Timur and all of that.

00:58:26.080 --> 00:58:30.720
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, one wonders what is the popular culture of the time and where do you learn

00:58:30.720 --> 00:58:31.920
[Amit Varma]: your history from?

00:58:31.920 --> 00:58:36.520
[Amit Varma]: And yet, you know, people like Alexander and Timur are clearly examples.

00:58:36.520 --> 00:58:40.920
[Amit Varma]: How much of this would have sort of played a part in Dara's becoming who he was like

00:58:40.920 --> 00:58:46.200
[Amit Varma]: one is he's wrestling with these dual imperatives of very early real world imperative or watch

00:58:46.200 --> 00:58:51.440
[Amit Varma]: out for your brothers and do what you gotta do to, you know, be the next big boy.

00:58:51.440 --> 00:58:55.340
[Amit Varma]: And the other one is that whole intellectual and spiritual quest he's on.

00:58:55.340 --> 00:59:00.280
[Amit Varma]: And some of it comes from phobias like Alexander, like maybe Timur in terms of the sort of empirary

00:59:00.280 --> 00:59:04.560
[Amit Varma]: wars or even Akbar, though, as you say, he doesn't acknowledge Akbar much, but even Akbar

00:59:04.560 --> 00:59:10.520
[Amit Varma]: in terms of the syncretism and the way he sort of is open to other cultures.

00:59:10.520 --> 00:59:15.520
[Amit Varma]: Is there a sense that these made a difference to Dara Shikoh in shaping him, the person

00:59:15.520 --> 00:59:17.360
[Amit Varma]: he was and what he went on to become?

00:59:17.360 --> 00:59:18.360
[Guest]: Yes, absolutely.

00:59:18.360 --> 00:59:23.560
[Guest]: So all of these were models for Timurid kings.

00:59:23.560 --> 00:59:28.720
[Guest]: And you know, you're right in that they weren't printed books, the way we have printed today.

00:59:28.720 --> 00:59:33.200
[Guest]: So books didn't, they were expensive, they didn't circulate in the same way.

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:36.120
[Guest]: But books are very important.

00:59:36.120 --> 00:59:42.560
[Guest]: You know, the invention of writing and of the written codex, you know, meant that you

00:59:42.560 --> 00:59:47.280
[Guest]: could you could really have the whole world between two covers, you know, in a sort of

00:59:47.280 --> 00:59:49.360
[Guest]: bundle of papers.

00:59:49.360 --> 00:59:56.560
[Guest]: And more libraries, of course, also famous, Dara Shikoh had the advantage of several generations

00:59:56.560 --> 00:59:57.560
[Guest]: of collection.

00:59:57.560 --> 01:00:03.480
[Guest]: He also, you know, got his own, acquired his own manuscripts and sponsored the copying

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:04.480
[Guest]: of others.

01:00:04.480 --> 01:00:08.480
[Guest]: So books did circulate, you know, they just not to the extent that they do, but they did

01:00:08.480 --> 01:00:09.480
[Guest]: circulate.

01:00:09.480 --> 01:00:17.160
[Guest]: And we can see that ideas circulated and ideas spilled out of books and circulated and permeated

01:00:17.160 --> 01:00:19.320
[Guest]: the popular imagination.

01:00:19.320 --> 01:00:26.960
[Guest]: So the idea of Alexander as a powerful conqueror, and as a powerful conqueror, he also was successful

01:00:26.960 --> 01:00:27.960
[Guest]: in India.

01:00:27.960 --> 01:00:28.960
[Guest]: He overpowered Indians.

01:00:28.960 --> 01:00:31.320
[Guest]: So there's that.

01:00:31.320 --> 01:00:36.720
[Guest]: And he also was a philosophical ruler, he would have dialogues, a kind of Darbar sort

01:00:36.720 --> 01:00:42.120
[Guest]: of similar to the dialogues that Akbar had with philosophers in his Abadadkhana.

01:00:42.120 --> 01:00:47.280
[Guest]: So these dual roles of Alexander came to be very important.

01:00:47.280 --> 01:00:52.400
[Guest]: And I think Alexander is one of the overlooked models for the Mughal, the Indian Timurid

01:00:52.400 --> 01:00:53.680
[Guest]: kings.

01:00:53.680 --> 01:01:01.160
[Guest]: So these past figures were very, very important for Mughal rulers, and they were constantly

01:01:01.160 --> 01:01:02.160
[Guest]: invoked.

01:01:02.160 --> 01:01:07.240
[Guest]: Definitely Temur, you know, Temur is one of them, you know, somebody who Shah Jahan very

01:01:07.240 --> 01:01:13.560
[Guest]: consciously modelled himself on, and, you know, helped circulate his spurious memoirs

01:01:13.560 --> 01:01:18.600
[Guest]: that gained a lot of popularity, but honestly, he never vanishes.

01:01:18.600 --> 01:01:23.800
[Guest]: It becomes very common for people to talk about the second Sikandar, you know, you might

01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:30.760
[Guest]: even have heard that, you know, so one of the bitter ironies of the story, and one reason

01:01:30.760 --> 01:01:35.640
[Guest]: why I bring up Alexander at the beginning, in the context of Jahangir and the dialogues

01:01:35.640 --> 01:01:40.320
[Guest]: that are taking place at Jahangir's court, is because, yes, of course, this both sides

01:01:40.320 --> 01:01:47.080
[Guest]: of Alexander to different degrees become important for Shah Jahan's sons, and for Dara Shukoh,

01:01:47.080 --> 01:01:51.120
[Guest]: and then you know that, you know, that of course, so Alexander defeats Darius, you know,

01:01:51.120 --> 01:01:54.440
[Guest]: the emperor whom Dara is also named for.

01:01:54.440 --> 01:02:00.240
[Guest]: And then finally, after the Battle of Samogar, you know, there's a poet who says, now in

01:02:00.240 --> 01:02:04.120
[Guest]: this case, you have the second, the Sikandar, who is defeating Dara.

01:02:04.120 --> 01:02:09.280
[Guest]: So that becomes, so there is this bitter irony that, you know, we have Dara Shukoh, who is

01:02:09.280 --> 01:02:18.640
[Guest]: modeling himself on Alexander, you know, on Alexander as a portrait in Persian poetry.

01:02:18.640 --> 01:02:24.760
[Guest]: And then, then we actually have Aurangzeb, who truly becomes the second Sikandar and

01:02:24.760 --> 01:02:26.320
[Guest]: defeats his brother Dara.

01:02:26.320 --> 01:02:30.120
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk a bit about the religious landscape of the time, like another sort of false binary

01:02:30.120 --> 01:02:35.080
[Amit Varma]: that seems to have come down is that, you know, is of orthodox Islam, the Sunnis on

01:02:35.080 --> 01:02:39.880
[Amit Varma]: the one side, and then you have the Sufis on the other side, who don't really, you know,

01:02:39.880 --> 01:02:43.580
[Amit Varma]: believe in all of those conventions and are much more free flowing, so to say.

01:02:43.580 --> 01:02:47.560
[Amit Varma]: As you point out, this isn't quite true, like you refer to how Dara Shukoh in his first

01:02:47.560 --> 01:02:52.920
[Amit Varma]: book Safina Tulaliya assigned himself as Muhammad Dara Shukoh, Hanafi Qadiri.

01:02:52.920 --> 01:02:57.880
[Amit Varma]: And Hanafi, of course, as a nod to the orthodox elements in Qadiri is, you know, one of the

01:02:57.880 --> 01:02:58.880
[Amit Varma]: Sufi strands.

01:02:58.880 --> 01:03:03.320
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, sort of point Qadiri, and therefore sort of pointing out that there's nothing

01:03:03.320 --> 01:03:05.960
[Amit Varma]: incongruous about those going together.

01:03:05.960 --> 01:03:08.800
[Amit Varma]: And you speak of sort of the interplay between that.

01:03:08.800 --> 01:03:13.880
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about that landscape and how the sort of explorations that Dara

01:03:13.880 --> 01:03:18.600
[Amit Varma]: Shukoh was making, were they as unusual as they are made out to be today?

01:03:18.600 --> 01:03:21.240
[Amit Varma]: Or was it all par for the course in those times?

01:03:21.240 --> 01:03:29.080
[Guest]: So I would say both things are true in that, yes, there were sections at the court who

01:03:29.080 --> 01:03:32.720
[Guest]: might have been disapproving of what Dara Shukoh engaged in.

01:03:32.720 --> 01:03:36.800
[Guest]: It was also hard to say, you know, who an alim was, who is a member of the ulema.

01:03:36.800 --> 01:03:42.640
[Guest]: You know, if you look at any kind of modern Bollywood movie on the mobiles, then you might

01:03:42.640 --> 01:03:48.840
[Guest]: see these kind of black robed people who are always like plucking and tuck-tutting about

01:03:48.840 --> 01:03:54.200
[Guest]: things that are going on, you know, say Emperor Akbar has a wife and she's doing puja, you

01:03:54.200 --> 01:03:57.160
[Guest]: know, and then like, they get really upset about that.

01:03:57.160 --> 01:04:05.920
[Guest]: So you know, a very easily visible group who don't stand for pluralism, you know, who are

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:07.960
[Guest]: very close minded.

01:04:07.960 --> 01:04:11.800
[Guest]: And this stems from modern developments.

01:04:11.800 --> 01:04:19.640
[Guest]: So the idea of the ulema as a very closed social group who are separate from Sufis is

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:23.440
[Guest]: something that happens at a later stage in South Asia.

01:04:23.440 --> 01:04:30.560
[Guest]: Now at this stage in the 17th century, a lot of, you know, who, you know, an alim, a member

01:04:30.560 --> 01:04:34.320
[Guest]: of the ulema, is really, is a learned person.

01:04:34.320 --> 01:04:37.720
[Guest]: And a lot of these people had roles at the court.

01:04:37.720 --> 01:04:42.960
[Guest]: So they juggled multiple tasks and responsibilities.

01:04:42.960 --> 01:04:47.280
[Guest]: And many of them had initiation in different Sufi orders.

01:04:47.280 --> 01:04:55.200
[Guest]: So the idea of a Sufism that, again, is more tolerant, heterodox, and it's totally separate

01:04:55.200 --> 01:05:02.760
[Guest]: from the more judicial world, legalistic world of the ulema, is not something that we see

01:05:02.760 --> 01:05:09.880
[Guest]: when we look at the court chronicles and when we look at lists of who an alim is, for instance.

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:14.800
[Guest]: So they might have a list of the ulema and the hukama and the fuzala, you know, so the

01:05:14.800 --> 01:05:17.960
[Guest]: people who are considered to be learned.

01:05:17.960 --> 01:05:21.400
[Guest]: And you know, these could be physicians.

01:05:21.400 --> 01:05:26.040
[Guest]: These could be people who are well versed in Islamic law, but they also have initiation

01:05:26.040 --> 01:05:27.560
[Guest]: in a Sufi order.

01:05:27.560 --> 01:05:33.960
[Guest]: One such person could have, his main job could be managing the emperor's household, you know,

01:05:33.960 --> 01:05:34.960
[Guest]: as well.

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:39.400
[Guest]: So it's not as though there, you know, there was like the separate like room or council

01:05:39.400 --> 01:05:43.000
[Guest]: of ulema who didn't have other worldly responsibilities.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:47.760
[Guest]: And you know, their sole job was to release what was acceptable and respectable and what

01:05:47.760 --> 01:05:48.760
[Guest]: wasn't.

01:05:48.760 --> 01:05:53.600
[Guest]: At the same time, there were different strands of thought, you know, amongst Sufis also.

01:05:53.600 --> 01:05:58.680
[Guest]: There were Sufis who leaned towards the more ecstatic sides of the side of things.

01:05:58.680 --> 01:06:08.600
[Guest]: For instance, those who enjoyed or propagated listening to music, musical audition.

01:06:08.600 --> 01:06:14.040
[Guest]: And then there were Sufis who espoused a more sober form of religiosity.

01:06:14.040 --> 01:06:18.640
[Guest]: So there were definitely divisions, but the divisions did not fall along the lines of

01:06:18.640 --> 01:06:20.680
[Amit Varma]: Sufis versus ulema.

01:06:20.680 --> 01:06:24.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, having looked at Dara Shikoh, let's also talk about Aurangzeb, because one of

01:06:24.240 --> 01:06:28.040
[Amit Varma]: the things you sort of demonstrate in your book as well is that the traditional view

01:06:28.040 --> 01:06:34.840
[Amit Varma]: of him as this austere religious bigot who did not, you know, who was extremely orthodox,

01:06:34.840 --> 01:06:42.080
[Amit Varma]: did not have any regard for the arts and all of that is not quite true either.

01:06:42.080 --> 01:06:46.440
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about the young Aurangzeb, especially again, I was sort of struck trying

01:06:46.440 --> 01:06:53.080
[Amit Varma]: to, by the glimpses one got of the human aspects of him, for example, just as, you know, Dara

01:06:53.080 --> 01:06:57.080
[Amit Varma]: is close to his elder sister Jahanara and they share so many of the same interests in

01:06:57.080 --> 01:07:00.880
[Amit Varma]: terms of religion and all of that.

01:07:00.880 --> 01:07:04.560
[Amit Varma]: We find that Aurangzeb is also close to Jahanara and he's always, you know, going and meeting

01:07:04.560 --> 01:07:06.840
[Amit Varma]: her and obviously regards her very much.

01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:12.920
[Amit Varma]: And there's also a sense where you speak about how, you know, Dara's sort of in court in

01:07:12.920 --> 01:07:18.920
[Amit Varma]: Lahore and Aurangzeb has, you know, is visiting from somewhere else.

01:07:18.920 --> 01:07:23.320
[Amit Varma]: And he's very upset because Dara is not giving him the importance he feels he deserves.

01:07:23.320 --> 01:07:28.040
[Amit Varma]: It's almost as if he wants his elder brother to sort of, you know, to love him almost,

01:07:28.040 --> 01:07:29.040
[Amit Varma]: you know.

01:07:29.040 --> 01:07:34.600
[Amit Varma]: What's the sense that you got of Aurangzeb as an individual during these young years

01:07:34.600 --> 01:07:37.320
[Amit Varma]: who's also growing up and trying to find his identity?

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:38.320
[Amit Varma]: What's his journey like?

01:07:38.320 --> 01:07:43.120
[Guest]: So the thing with Aurangzeb is because he becomes emperor later on.

01:07:43.120 --> 01:07:49.200
[Guest]: So anything that he wrote is of high value and is preserved and circulated.

01:07:49.200 --> 01:07:55.320
[Guest]: So we have a whole range of letters that Aurangzeb has written and these letters get collected

01:07:55.320 --> 01:07:57.880
[Guest]: and they circulate later on.

01:07:57.880 --> 01:08:02.200
[Guest]: So, you know, so we don't have them necessarily all of them like directly from Aurangzeb,

01:08:02.200 --> 01:08:03.200
[Guest]: you know, with the seal.

01:08:03.200 --> 01:08:07.240
[Guest]: We don't have those original documents, but you have the letters as they are preserved

01:08:07.240 --> 01:08:11.640
[Guest]: in later collections, collections that were made during his lifetime.

01:08:11.640 --> 01:08:17.480
[Guest]: So we do, we have that advantage in that we can see his own personal, we can hear his

01:08:17.480 --> 01:08:23.000
[Guest]: own personal voice more clearly than we can a lot of the other mughals.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:28.120
[Guest]: And through these letters, we see that there are a number of letters he writes to his elder

01:08:28.120 --> 01:08:29.840
[Guest]: sister Jahanara.

01:08:29.840 --> 01:08:34.360
[Guest]: The popular perception is that he was close to Roshanara, Dara Shukoh was close to Jahanara

01:08:34.360 --> 01:08:38.600
[Guest]: and Murad was close to Goharara and, you know, so there were these different factions that

01:08:38.600 --> 01:08:39.600
[Guest]: were formed.

01:08:39.600 --> 01:08:45.640
[Guest]: And we really see Jahanara's role as family peacemaker.

01:08:45.640 --> 01:08:48.800
[Guest]: She maintains a good relationship with all her brothers.

01:08:48.800 --> 01:08:50.760
[Guest]: She really goes out of her way to do that.

01:08:50.760 --> 01:08:56.240
[Guest]: She goes out of her way to try to smooth over any difficulties that they might have, tries

01:08:56.240 --> 01:09:01.080
[Guest]: to entertain meetings between them, for instance, and, you know, perhaps she engineers reconciliation

01:09:01.080 --> 01:09:07.080
[Guest]: or tries to between Dara and Aurangzeb when Dara is serving as governor of Lahore.

01:09:07.080 --> 01:09:11.960
[Guest]: And we get glimpses of like the sisterly relationship that she has with Aurangzeb.

01:09:11.960 --> 01:09:15.000
[Guest]: She's always writing to him more than he writes to her.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:19.000
[Guest]: She's sending him various gifts, you know, murabbas and, you know, like various like

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:26.720
[Guest]: treats and delicacies, you know, so we get a sense of the human side of Aurangzeb through

01:09:26.720 --> 01:09:31.360
[Guest]: these affectionate letters that he writes to his sister.

01:09:31.360 --> 01:09:36.280
[Guest]: And we also get a sense of his grievances.

01:09:36.280 --> 01:09:40.480
[Guest]: That also has to do with the nature of the sources because a lot of the argument that

01:09:40.480 --> 01:09:48.280
[Guest]: is made later on to justify Dara Shukoh's murder and Aurangzeb's accession to the throne

01:09:48.280 --> 01:09:53.360
[Guest]: is that Dara Shukoh was really, apart from the fact that, you know, he was supposed to

01:09:53.360 --> 01:09:59.280
[Guest]: be an infidel and so on, that Dara Shukoh was not really a good son and a good brother.

01:09:59.280 --> 01:10:06.160
[Guest]: He was, he took over at the helm of affairs from his father, he was not fair to his brothers.

01:10:06.160 --> 01:10:11.760
[Guest]: So that could also color the kinds of sources that are later preserved and circulated that

01:10:11.760 --> 01:10:15.200
[Guest]: show Aurangzeb to be a sensitive sibling.

01:10:15.200 --> 01:10:24.240
[Guest]: At the same time, you know, we do get a sense, you know, that he enjoyed listening to music

01:10:24.240 --> 01:10:30.760
[Guest]: when he was a prince, he might have, you know, there is this album that's associated with

01:10:30.760 --> 01:10:35.280
[Guest]: him, like supposed to be a stunning album of art, if indeed it is found and found to

01:10:35.280 --> 01:10:41.520
[Guest]: be authentic, that would give us an amazing picture of his own artistic sponsorship and

01:10:41.520 --> 01:10:44.320
[Guest]: interest when he was a prince.

01:10:44.320 --> 01:10:50.360
[Guest]: So in these regards, he was not so different from other Mughal princes who were patrons

01:10:50.360 --> 01:10:58.320
[Guest]: of the arts and so on, you know, they cultivated their own aesthetic side as just part of being

01:10:58.320 --> 01:11:00.560
[Guest]: elite Mughals.

01:11:00.560 --> 01:11:06.040
[Guest]: He did temper that later on, you know, partly to show himself in contrast to his brother,

01:11:06.040 --> 01:11:11.880
[Guest]: you know, so he, there was a change, there's definitely, you know, like far less sponsorship

01:11:11.880 --> 01:11:16.680
[Guest]: of cultural activities when he was emperor.

01:11:16.680 --> 01:11:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And one of the thoughts that kind of struck me while reading the book was that in one

01:11:22.480 --> 01:11:27.600
[Amit Varma]: curious aspect, Aurangzeb reminded me of Indira Gandhi, in the sense that when Indira Gandhi

01:11:27.600 --> 01:11:33.520
[Amit Varma]: needed to rebrand herself and distinguish herself from the syndicate in the late 1960s,

01:11:33.520 --> 01:11:37.960
[Amit Varma]: she took this massive leftward turn to set herself apart, because that was the only way

01:11:37.960 --> 01:11:40.600
[Amit Varma]: to sort of distinguish herself as a brand.

01:11:40.600 --> 01:11:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that in some ways, would it be fair to say that, you know, those could

01:11:46.080 --> 01:11:54.960
[Amit Varma]: be the imperatives behind Aurangzeb also moving in that more doctrinaire, sort of rigid direction

01:11:54.960 --> 01:12:01.120
[Amit Varma]: to distinguish himself from his main rival for the throne, which was Dara Shago and even

01:12:01.120 --> 01:12:04.480
[Amit Varma]: perhaps to some extent from his father.

01:12:04.480 --> 01:12:09.360
[Amit Varma]: So would you say that those incentives also kind of came into play?

01:12:09.360 --> 01:12:15.080
[Guest]: Most definitely, you know, I think, I think it took Aurangzeb a little while to fully

01:12:15.080 --> 01:12:21.080
[Guest]: define himself by abandoning the traditions of his forebears, you know, whether it's the

01:12:21.080 --> 01:12:25.400
[Guest]: Jharkha Darshan, you know, where the emperor kind of sits and has, you know, everyone view

01:12:25.400 --> 01:12:32.920
[Guest]: him at this Jharkha, which is an institution that Akbar really established and popularized.

01:12:32.920 --> 01:12:36.240
[Guest]: So it took him a while, you know, it didn't all happen overnight.

01:12:36.240 --> 01:12:40.640
[Guest]: But there was this process by which, you know, even during the struggle for succession, you

01:12:40.640 --> 01:12:45.920
[Guest]: can see that there are some insinuations about heresy on the part of Dara Shago.

01:12:45.920 --> 01:12:51.320
[Guest]: And these insinuations get solidified once he becomes emperor so that he does have a

01:12:51.320 --> 01:12:53.520
[Guest]: solid case that's built up.

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:59.000
[Guest]: And he then has his own very austere model of kingship that again is a departure from

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:00.880
[Amit Varma]: his ancestors.

01:13:00.880 --> 01:13:04.600
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking aloud, would it be then fair to say that wherever you have this sort

01:13:04.600 --> 01:13:09.920
[Amit Varma]: of a conflict, it's bound to be a polarizing one and it's bound to drive people towards

01:13:09.920 --> 01:13:10.920
[Amit Varma]: the extremes?

01:13:10.920 --> 01:13:15.280
[Amit Varma]: Like you could argue that, you know, Aurangzeb might have been not as extreme as he was,

01:13:15.280 --> 01:13:16.920
[Amit Varma]: but he felt the need to define himself.

01:13:16.920 --> 01:13:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, in modern times, if you look at Pakistan, would it be fair to say that to

01:13:20.720 --> 01:13:26.320
[Amit Varma]: some extent, they are shaped by their need to define themselves in opposition to what

01:13:26.320 --> 01:13:27.800
[Amit Varma]: India is, for example?

01:13:27.800 --> 01:13:32.960
[Guest]: Yes, you know, I think that's, that's really happening on both sides, you know, just take

01:13:32.960 --> 01:13:38.520
[Guest]: language, for instance, the way in which the Urdu language has developed in Pakistan, official

01:13:38.520 --> 01:13:44.080
[Guest]: Urdu, is highly Persianized, there are a lot of Persian and Arabic neologisms, there are

01:13:44.080 --> 01:13:49.640
[Guest]: many ways in which there's an attempt to look westwards, to look at West Asia, you know,

01:13:49.640 --> 01:13:54.360
[Guest]: for cultural models, as opposed to India, of course, one can't totally sort of build

01:13:54.360 --> 01:13:55.360
[Guest]: a wall.

01:13:55.360 --> 01:14:01.360
[Guest]: There are still lots of commonalities and lots of cultural interactions, you know, similarly

01:14:01.360 --> 01:14:09.520
[Guest]: with the official Hindi that is used in television and in officialdom in India today, that these

01:14:09.520 --> 01:14:14.920
[Guest]: Hindi and Urdu have become two languages that are not so easily mutually intelligible, for

01:14:14.920 --> 01:14:18.880
[Guest]: the language that people speak often, you know, falls in the middle of the spectrum.

01:14:18.880 --> 01:14:23.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, I traveled through Pakistan while covering a cricket tour in 2006, and I spent a month

01:14:23.440 --> 01:14:24.440
[Amit Varma]: and a half there.

01:14:24.440 --> 01:14:28.480
[Amit Varma]: And apart from the Urdu signs, it didn't feel like I was in a foreign country and the language

01:14:28.480 --> 01:14:32.840
[Amit Varma]: is exactly the same and I was sort of aware of, you know, the Hindi nationalism, so to

01:14:32.840 --> 01:14:37.000
[Amit Varma]: say, and how Shuddh Hindi is such an artificial construct and has been modeled out of that

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:40.800
[Amit Varma]: I wasn't aware that there's a similar process happening with Urdu in Pakistan.

01:14:40.800 --> 01:14:45.920
[Amit Varma]: In fact, just thinking aloud, you know, when I watch Prime Minister Modi's 8pm speeches

01:14:45.920 --> 01:14:51.080
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, and it strikes me that the kind of Hindi that he uses very deliberately,

01:14:51.080 --> 01:14:55.360
[Amit Varma]: is that kind of Shuddh Hindi which people don't speak and therefore I'm sort of kind

01:14:55.360 --> 01:15:01.400
[Amit Varma]: of baffled by the immense popularity because he's not actually speaking even the language

01:15:01.400 --> 01:15:02.880
[Amit Varma]: of the Hindi heartland.

01:15:02.880 --> 01:15:07.020
[Amit Varma]: He's speaking this very Shuddh Hindi, which people don't speak in their everyday lives

01:15:07.020 --> 01:15:10.280
[Amit Varma]: from my experience, so I was but that's, that's an aside.

01:15:10.280 --> 01:15:13.720
[Amit Varma]: Kind of moving on, you know, and again, earlier, I spoke about how it seemed to me through

01:15:13.720 --> 01:15:20.080
[Amit Varma]: the book that you have sort of Tara evolving in stages where, you know, initially, it felt

01:15:20.080 --> 01:15:23.640
[Amit Varma]: like a spiritual journey, and then there's an intellectual ballast to it.

01:15:23.640 --> 01:15:25.680
[Amit Varma]: And he writes these different books.

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:31.320
[Amit Varma]: And then after he's comes back from his failed conquest of Kandahar, there is this deeper

01:15:31.320 --> 01:15:36.280
[Amit Varma]: turn and this engagement with the Indic philosophies, which wasn't there earlier.

01:15:36.280 --> 01:15:41.120
[Amit Varma]: I mean, more specifically, the project of translating the Upanishads into Persian.

01:15:41.120 --> 01:15:45.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, he even had a theory that the Upanishads were the lost book mentioned in the Quran,

01:15:45.240 --> 01:15:46.240
[Amit Varma]: for example.

01:15:46.240 --> 01:15:47.880
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that phase.

01:15:47.880 --> 01:15:52.960
[Amit Varma]: And what do you think drove that phase because it doesn't seem to be, you know, like it's

01:15:52.960 --> 01:15:59.280
[Amit Varma]: been speculated that part of it was because he was trying to get alliances among the Rajputs

01:15:59.280 --> 01:16:01.160
[Amit Varma]: and he wanted to portray that image.

01:16:01.160 --> 01:16:04.660
[Amit Varma]: But this seems a bit too far to go for the sake of posturing.

01:16:04.660 --> 01:16:08.480
[Amit Varma]: And also the fact of the matter, as you've pointed out, is that, you know, the Rajputs

01:16:08.480 --> 01:16:12.480
[Amit Varma]: were equally divided in Aurangzeb's camp as in Dara Shikoh's camp.

01:16:12.480 --> 01:16:16.760
[Amit Varma]: This is simply a post facto binary we have kind of invented.

01:16:16.760 --> 01:16:22.320
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about his new deepening interest into sort of the Indic philosophies.

01:16:22.320 --> 01:16:25.720
[Guest]: So I think there are a couple of things going on here.

01:16:25.720 --> 01:16:31.840
[Guest]: One is the deepening and widening of Dara Shikoh's own spiritual intellectual interests,

01:16:31.840 --> 01:16:37.400
[Guest]: which come from a genuine curiosity and also a kind of restlessness.

01:16:37.400 --> 01:16:45.800
[Guest]: So Dara Shikoh is, he feels that he has perhaps had his fill of Sufism, not, you know, not

01:16:45.800 --> 01:16:50.960
[Guest]: in the sense that he's kind of completed, but he's already ascended these amazing spiritual

01:16:50.960 --> 01:16:53.440
[Guest]: heights.

01:16:53.440 --> 01:16:54.720
[Guest]: He's done what he can.

01:16:54.720 --> 01:16:59.000
[Guest]: He's now speaking not as a disciple, but he's really speaking as a master who is giving

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:00.800
[Guest]: instruction on the Sufi path.

01:17:00.800 --> 01:17:05.640
[Guest]: And you can see seeds of his interest in Indic thought.

01:17:05.640 --> 01:17:13.400
[Guest]: And there's already a basis for this, because in Sufi writings and poetry, there is the

01:17:13.400 --> 01:17:16.920
[Guest]: celebration of what is not Islam.

01:17:16.920 --> 01:17:22.760
[Guest]: There's the celebration of what is called kufr, you know, or infidelity.

01:17:22.760 --> 01:17:27.040
[Guest]: And the celebration is something that's, it's really complicated, you know, it doesn't mean

01:17:27.040 --> 01:17:35.320
[Guest]: that everyone has to go out and just do things that are completely against religion.

01:17:35.320 --> 01:17:43.240
[Guest]: But the poetry, certain Sufi writings, give a space for this in order to really ascend

01:17:43.240 --> 01:17:49.240
[Guest]: higher spiritual levels and metaphorically see the countenance of the beloved, you know,

01:17:49.240 --> 01:17:50.240
[Guest]: which is the divine.

01:17:50.240 --> 01:17:53.640
[Guest]: So Dara Shukh was already, you know, even before this, he's reaching out to other Sufi

01:17:53.640 --> 01:17:54.640
[Guest]: masters.

01:17:54.640 --> 01:17:59.240
[Guest]: You know, he's achieved what he's wanted to with the Qadavis and his sister and his father

01:17:59.240 --> 01:18:02.840
[Guest]: continue their relationship with them and so does Dara, but you know, Dara doesn't stay

01:18:02.840 --> 01:18:03.840
[Guest]: with that.

01:18:03.840 --> 01:18:10.160
[Guest]: You know, he writes to other people and what he doesn't want to do is to go into the real

01:18:10.160 --> 01:18:16.640
[Guest]: nitty gritties of philosophical Sufism, which he can if he wants to, you know, this famous

01:18:16.640 --> 01:18:22.640
[Guest]: Andalusian mystic, Ibn Arabi, whose very, very complex and abstruse Arabic writings

01:18:22.640 --> 01:18:27.680
[Guest]: have been translated and commented upon in India, in the Indian subcontinent.

01:18:27.680 --> 01:18:32.320
[Guest]: One of the most famous interpreters of Ibn Arabi is Sheikh Muhibbullah Elahabadi, with

01:18:32.320 --> 01:18:34.160
[Guest]: whom Dara has a correspondence.

01:18:34.160 --> 01:18:39.320
[Guest]: And Dara Shukh wants something that's a little more transgressive and perhaps a little less

01:18:39.320 --> 01:18:44.400
[Guest]: arduous than kind of sitting and, you know, like understanding these really difficult

01:18:44.400 --> 01:18:45.400
[Guest]: texts.

01:18:45.400 --> 01:18:48.960
[Guest]: So he starts getting interested in Indic thought, and there's already a tradition of that.

01:18:48.960 --> 01:18:54.480
[Guest]: And there are already several yogic ideas that have been incorporated into Chishti mysticism.

01:18:54.480 --> 01:18:59.040
[Guest]: And you know, it could be that the Qadavis also have some association with that.

01:18:59.040 --> 01:19:01.200
[Guest]: And then he goes even deeper.

01:19:01.200 --> 01:19:07.080
[Guest]: So when he's coming back from Kandahar, he makes sure to stop and have dialogues with

01:19:07.080 --> 01:19:09.480
[Guest]: a Vaishnava ascetic called Baba Lal.

01:19:09.480 --> 01:19:10.480
[Guest]: And he has all these dialogues.

01:19:10.480 --> 01:19:15.720
[Guest]: So we have the results of those sessions written down, except that it doesn't seem that these

01:19:15.720 --> 01:19:19.040
[Guest]: are really the literal transcripts, there are many different versions of this.

01:19:19.040 --> 01:19:24.160
[Guest]: But we can see that Dara Shukh has acquainted himself with at least the Persian translations

01:19:24.160 --> 01:19:27.720
[Guest]: of the Ramayana and so on, and he has questions.

01:19:27.720 --> 01:19:33.440
[Guest]: And I think he finds his dialogues with Baba Lal inspiring enough that he continues and

01:19:33.440 --> 01:19:34.880
[Guest]: he goes further.

01:19:34.880 --> 01:19:41.320
[Guest]: And he's already compiled a collection of rather shocking, sort of transgressive, ecstatic

01:19:41.320 --> 01:19:47.960
[Guest]: sayings of Sufis, and he's included some non-Muslims in them, including Baba Lal.

01:19:47.960 --> 01:19:54.120
[Guest]: So once he's in Delhi, he starts branching out, and he already has access to a lot of

01:19:54.120 --> 01:19:58.880
[Guest]: works in the Mughal library, but he wants to patronize and sponsor more.

01:19:58.880 --> 01:20:03.040
[Guest]: And the other thing that's going on is that this is a time when both he and Aurangzeb

01:20:03.040 --> 01:20:10.240
[Guest]: are competing to really jockey for alliances and influence amongst Rajput rulers.

01:20:10.240 --> 01:20:15.800
[Guest]: So say there's some trouble brewing in Mewar, both of them want to try, they want to be

01:20:15.800 --> 01:20:20.600
[Guest]: the first ones to go there and to try to solve it, and they compete by sending their envoys,

01:20:20.600 --> 01:20:24.800
[Guest]: Brahmin envoys, like a sensitive choice, and messengers.

01:20:24.800 --> 01:20:30.200
[Guest]: And later on in the eve of the Battle of Succession, Aurangzeb is also telling Rana Raj, saying,

01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:35.400
[Guest]: I'm going to be like my illustrious forebears, I'm going to allow everyone to flourish in

01:20:35.400 --> 01:20:37.920
[Guest]: peace with their own religions, and so on.

01:20:37.920 --> 01:20:44.000
[Guest]: So Aurangzeb is making this very, very explicit gesture towards fostering an environment of

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:45.000
[Guest]: religious pluralism.

01:20:45.000 --> 01:20:51.320
[Guest]: And Dayaan Shukla is doing it in a less direct way, not that he's not interested, he is,

01:20:51.320 --> 01:20:58.840
[Guest]: but one can't wish away this backdrop where they each try to gain influence amongst the

01:20:58.840 --> 01:20:59.840
[Amit Varma]: Rajputs.

01:20:59.840 --> 01:21:04.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, all the historians that I've had on my show don't like counterfactuals so much.

01:21:04.720 --> 01:21:09.520
[Amit Varma]: It's only non historians who love to speculate about, you know, what would have happened

01:21:09.520 --> 01:21:12.240
[Amit Varma]: if this person did this and blah, blah, blah.

01:21:12.240 --> 01:21:17.240
[Amit Varma]: But nevertheless, given that there is such a dominant narrative around this particular

01:21:17.240 --> 01:21:21.880
[Amit Varma]: counterfactual given that, you know, Ashok referred to Dara Shukla's death as the partition

01:21:21.880 --> 01:21:26.480
[Amit Varma]: before partition, what is your sense of what kind of an emperor he would have been if he

01:21:26.480 --> 01:21:28.200
[Amit Varma]: had somehow managed to win?

01:21:28.200 --> 01:21:32.320
[Amit Varma]: Because really, his managing to win is a few lucky events here and there, like you point

01:21:32.320 --> 01:21:36.120
[Amit Varma]: out how when Aurangzeb when getting rid of one of the other brothers pretended he had

01:21:36.120 --> 01:21:39.040
[Amit Varma]: dysentery and called him to his tent and plied him with drink.

01:21:39.040 --> 01:21:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Now Aurangzeb could actually have gotten dysentery and died right in those times.

01:21:43.080 --> 01:21:46.080
[Amit Varma]: So if Dara Shukla ends up as emperor, what's your brief sense?

01:21:46.080 --> 01:21:50.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you've already pointed out that he was like a sort of a co-ruler for a long time

01:21:50.280 --> 01:21:54.280
[Amit Varma]: by Shah Jahan's side, and wouldn't have been very different from Aurangzeb because he would

01:21:54.280 --> 01:21:59.520
[Amit Varma]: have followed the imperatives of politics and he would have had to kill all his brothers.

01:21:59.520 --> 01:22:03.960
[Amit Varma]: Probably I think in the book, you mentioned that when his son, Suleiman is chasing his

01:22:03.960 --> 01:22:07.800
[Amit Varma]: brother Shuja across the border, he tells him bring me back his head, something to that

01:22:07.800 --> 01:22:08.800
[Amit Varma]: effect.

01:22:08.800 --> 01:22:09.800
[Amit Varma]: So all of that would have happened.

01:22:09.800 --> 01:22:14.040
[Amit Varma]: But in terms of the Indian subcontinent, would it have made a difference or would the larger

01:22:14.040 --> 01:22:17.600
[Amit Varma]: currents of history have continued going more or less the way they did?

01:22:17.600 --> 01:22:18.600
[Guest]: So it's a difficult question.

01:22:18.600 --> 01:22:22.640
[Guest]: Of course, one thing to keep in mind is that when the war of succession broke out, Shah

01:22:22.640 --> 01:22:26.520
[Guest]: Jahan was ill, he was possibly severely ill.

01:22:26.520 --> 01:22:32.200
[Guest]: I actually had a well-known medical specialist from Yale kind of give me his take on what

01:22:32.200 --> 01:22:36.080
[Guest]: Shah Jahan's illness might have been, but he survives.

01:22:36.080 --> 01:22:38.400
[Guest]: He survives for many years after that.

01:22:38.400 --> 01:22:43.640
[Guest]: So Dara would not have been official ruler right away, though he would have been a kind

01:22:43.640 --> 01:22:46.800
[Guest]: of co-ruler or proxy ruler along with his father.

01:22:46.800 --> 01:22:53.280
[Guest]: So I think perhaps that period of time would have also helped him learn the ropes better

01:22:53.280 --> 01:22:54.480
[Guest]: of rule.

01:22:54.480 --> 01:23:00.400
[Guest]: He would have tried to be a sacred ruler in the model, again, of his forebears, in the

01:23:00.400 --> 01:23:02.840
[Guest]: model of Akbar.

01:23:02.840 --> 01:23:08.240
[Guest]: In terms of the broader structural problems of the Mughal Empire, whether what Irfan Habib

01:23:08.240 --> 01:23:15.680
[Guest]: has termed the agrarian crisis, the very costly Deccan expansions, for instance, the other

01:23:15.680 --> 01:23:19.640
[Guest]: foreign adventures that Shah Jahan liked to fund.

01:23:19.640 --> 01:23:24.480
[Guest]: So these were all serious issues, and it's hard to see how Dara Shukoh might have prevented

01:23:24.480 --> 01:23:26.200
[Guest]: that, if at all.

01:23:26.200 --> 01:23:27.200
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:23:27.200 --> 01:23:31.320
[Amit Varma]: I think we've spoken a lot about your book, and I'll leave it to readers to read it for

01:23:31.320 --> 01:23:32.320
[Amit Varma]: themselves.

01:23:32.320 --> 01:23:33.320
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I highly recommend it.

01:23:33.320 --> 01:23:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to what you're working on now.

01:23:36.920 --> 01:23:40.560
[Amit Varma]: The book was finished a while back, and of course, there is that whole release cycle

01:23:40.560 --> 01:23:43.720
[Amit Varma]: and you have to go around promoting it and all of that.

01:23:43.720 --> 01:23:45.100
[Amit Varma]: But what are you working on now?

01:23:45.100 --> 01:23:46.100
[Amit Varma]: What preoccupies you?

01:23:46.100 --> 01:23:52.560
[Guest]: I'm working on a book that, in some indirect ways, is a sequel to this, except that it's

01:23:52.560 --> 01:23:59.760
[Guest]: not about Aurangzeb, and it's more a history of ideas than a biography of one particular

01:23:59.760 --> 01:24:00.760
[Guest]: person.

01:24:00.760 --> 01:24:06.280
[Guest]: But the reason why it's connected to this book is because part of the idea starts by

01:24:06.280 --> 01:24:14.200
[Guest]: seeing what happens to Dara Shukoh's writings, and that's something that I hint in the epilogue.

01:24:14.200 --> 01:24:18.680
[Guest]: So Aurangzeb did do his best to efface traces of Dara Shukoh.

01:24:18.680 --> 01:24:26.600
[Guest]: He didn't succeed completely, and later rulers and writers did try to complete the work.

01:24:26.600 --> 01:24:32.520
[Guest]: But what we see, if we look at the manuscripts and circulation of Persian manuscripts, is

01:24:32.520 --> 01:24:38.200
[Guest]: that there were lots and lots of people making out copies of Dara Shukoh's writings, circulating

01:24:38.200 --> 01:24:42.440
[Guest]: and reading them, and a lot of these happened to be Hindus.

01:24:42.440 --> 01:24:49.200
[Guest]: And in Aurangzeb, and even during Aurangzeb, you just see growing numbers of Hindus who

01:24:49.200 --> 01:24:51.800
[Guest]: were literate in Persian.

01:24:51.800 --> 01:24:58.520
[Guest]: So these came to form part of a socially privileged elite administrative class.

01:24:58.520 --> 01:25:05.000
[Guest]: There were often certain castes that we see that predominated, Kayas, Khatris, certain

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:06.000
[Guest]: Brahmins.

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:10.640
[Guest]: They were using Persian just like elite Indians use English today.

01:25:10.640 --> 01:25:18.080
[Guest]: English is seen as the passport to success, to a shot at a good upper-middle class life,

01:25:18.080 --> 01:25:19.080
[Guest]: social mobility.

01:25:19.080 --> 01:25:22.600
[Guest]: And at the same time, there are certain groups who are learning English.

01:25:22.600 --> 01:25:27.280
[Guest]: I mean, there's not all that much mobility, so the elites are reproducing themselves.

01:25:27.280 --> 01:25:32.560
[Guest]: And that's sort of what we see in the 17th and 18th centuries, but we see these growing

01:25:32.560 --> 01:25:37.760
[Guest]: numbers of Hindus who come to be part of the vast local bureaucracy, again, Aurangzeb expanded

01:25:37.760 --> 01:25:44.080
[Guest]: the bureaucracy, and these Hindus are looking for ways in which to access their sacred texts.

01:25:44.080 --> 01:25:47.600
[Guest]: And not all of them are Brahmins, and many of them don't know any Sanskrit.

01:25:47.600 --> 01:25:54.200
[Guest]: They might be, of course, conversant in Hindavi and various early forms of Hindi and so on.

01:25:54.200 --> 01:25:57.060
[Guest]: And they read in Persian, and they write in Persian, and many of them are reading and

01:25:57.060 --> 01:26:00.560
[Guest]: writing Dara Shukla's works, and they're also writing, producing their own works.

01:26:00.560 --> 01:26:03.680
[Guest]: They're producing their own religious texts in Persian.

01:26:03.680 --> 01:26:09.120
[Guest]: And these people come to be the intermediaries at the time of British colonialism.

01:26:09.120 --> 01:26:16.160
[Guest]: So we have the British winning the Battle of Plassey, trying to expand their hold over

01:26:16.160 --> 01:26:17.160
[Guest]: the subcontinent.

01:26:17.160 --> 01:26:19.960
[Guest]: And they also, they want to learn about the peoples over which they rule.

01:26:19.960 --> 01:26:24.960
[Guest]: They want to devise laws and so on to apply and use in their courts.

01:26:24.960 --> 01:26:30.680
[Guest]: And they, initially, Brahmins are reluctant to teach them Sanskrit, and they find people

01:26:30.680 --> 01:26:32.160
[Guest]: to teach them Persian.

01:26:32.160 --> 01:26:35.600
[Guest]: And Persian is the first language that they use for governing.

01:26:35.600 --> 01:26:42.960
[Guest]: So there is this whole class of munchies and translators, literatures, who are either tutors

01:26:42.960 --> 01:26:48.360
[Guest]: to colonial officials or informants to them, who are telling them about Indian customs

01:26:48.360 --> 01:26:51.960
[Guest]: and Indian religions, and this is what Hinduism is all about.

01:26:51.960 --> 01:26:57.960
[Guest]: And part of this is being shaped just by what colonial sponsors and patrons want to learn,

01:26:57.960 --> 01:27:01.800
[Guest]: and part of this is being shaped by what these informants are telling them.

01:27:01.800 --> 01:27:07.800
[Guest]: So there is this collaborative process that is creating a huge, huge body of work in Persian

01:27:07.800 --> 01:27:10.480
[Guest]: that is about religion in India.

01:27:10.480 --> 01:27:12.640
[Amit Varma]: And what's the impact of this work?

01:27:12.640 --> 01:27:16.840
[Guest]: So the impact of this is, it's shaping colonial policy.

01:27:16.840 --> 01:27:23.360
[Guest]: It's also shaping how Hindus, in this case, are presenting themselves and thinking about

01:27:23.360 --> 01:27:24.920
[Guest]: themselves.

01:27:24.920 --> 01:27:29.640
[Guest]: So it's in dialogue with other broader trends that are taking place, that would have taken

01:27:29.640 --> 01:27:33.800
[Guest]: place in the 18th century, regardless of colonialism.

01:27:33.800 --> 01:27:39.520
[Guest]: And it's also influenced by the kinds of things that colonial officials wanted to learn, and

01:27:39.520 --> 01:27:44.280
[Guest]: it's creating new centers of patronage, competing centers.

01:27:44.280 --> 01:27:50.960
[Guest]: So for instance, in the 18th century, we have Delhi being sacked, there are numerous attacks,

01:27:50.960 --> 01:27:56.840
[Guest]: of course, there are various Afghan attacks on Delhi, there are the Marathas, and then

01:27:56.840 --> 01:28:03.400
[Guest]: we have centers that are further east that are really gaining in prominence and in cultural

01:28:03.400 --> 01:28:04.400
[Guest]: vibrancy.

01:28:04.400 --> 01:28:10.360
[Guest]: Whether it's Fezabad or Lucknow or Benares, the population of Benares becomes double that

01:28:10.360 --> 01:28:11.360
[Guest]: of Delhi.

01:28:11.360 --> 01:28:14.120
[Guest]: We have Calcutta and so on.

01:28:14.120 --> 01:28:18.200
[Guest]: So we have all these centers that are becoming centers of patronage, and these are becoming

01:28:18.200 --> 01:28:24.200
[Guest]: hubs of Persian literature, like Benares, which we associate with Sanskrit and Sanskrit

01:28:24.200 --> 01:28:29.800
[Guest]: learning also becomes a hub of Persian, partly because of the East India Company and their

01:28:29.800 --> 01:28:33.800
[Guest]: interest in the region.

01:28:33.800 --> 01:28:37.840
[Guest]: And we have all these Hindus, this network of Hindus who are traveling, who are producing

01:28:37.840 --> 01:28:40.440
[Guest]: knowledge in Persian.

01:28:40.440 --> 01:28:47.240
[Guest]: And to me, this is an interesting angle on the prehistory of later developments.

01:28:47.240 --> 01:28:52.920
[Guest]: So it's often been neglected because it's the historians of the Mughal period of what's

01:28:52.920 --> 01:28:57.120
[Guest]: called medieval Indian history, but what we also call the early modern period, who tend

01:28:57.120 --> 01:28:58.120
[Guest]: to use Persian.

01:28:58.120 --> 01:29:03.280
[Guest]: And often historians of the modern period tend to look at sources in other languages.

01:29:03.280 --> 01:29:05.960
[Guest]: You know, again, not hard and fast rules, but these are the trends.

01:29:05.960 --> 01:29:13.720
[Guest]: So I wanted to see what certain elite Hindus were reading and writing, because I wanted

01:29:13.720 --> 01:29:18.280
[Guest]: to look at the history and trajectory of certain ideas.

01:29:18.280 --> 01:29:23.800
[Guest]: The idea of universalism, for instance, or the idea that there is a kind of core monotheistic

01:29:23.800 --> 01:29:26.680
[Guest]: essence to religion, no matter what you call it.

01:29:26.680 --> 01:29:30.800
[Guest]: Some people called it Sanatan Dharm, some people kind of just called it religion or

01:29:30.800 --> 01:29:32.000
[Guest]: the essence of Hinduism.

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:39.760
[Guest]: So it's the evolution of Hinduism into something that was stripped down, universal, that had

01:29:39.760 --> 01:29:46.240
[Guest]: its roots in Mughal Indology, and that also becomes sort of seen as the cultural matrix

01:29:46.240 --> 01:29:47.240
[Guest]: of India.

01:29:47.240 --> 01:29:51.240
[Guest]: So I find that Persian and Urdu sources are really an interesting lens through which to

01:29:51.240 --> 01:29:52.240
[Amit Varma]: look at that.

01:29:52.240 --> 01:29:57.520
[Amit Varma]: Would it then be the case that this sort of stripping down of Hinduism or, you know, getting

01:29:57.520 --> 01:30:01.680
[Amit Varma]: to broad core principles and all of that is happening partly because of the language?

01:30:01.680 --> 01:30:03.940
[Amit Varma]: Is the language shaping the content?

01:30:03.940 --> 01:30:08.640
[Amit Varma]: Is the fact that this is, you know, a bunch of Brahmins who are speaking and writing in

01:30:08.640 --> 01:30:11.920
[Amit Varma]: what is essentially till that point a foreign language?

01:30:11.920 --> 01:30:15.880
[Amit Varma]: Does it change the nature of the content that is being produced?

01:30:15.880 --> 01:30:21.240
[Amit Varma]: Is it more universal and say less insular than the content that might otherwise be produced

01:30:21.240 --> 01:30:25.360
[Amit Varma]: at that time in Sanskrit or Hindavi or whatever the local languages are?

01:30:25.360 --> 01:30:27.040
[Guest]: That's an interesting question.

01:30:27.040 --> 01:30:34.120
[Guest]: And I find that there are ways in which the language definitely shapes what's being produced.

01:30:34.120 --> 01:30:39.480
[Guest]: There are certain texts that are just more receptive to translation, but it doesn't entirely

01:30:39.480 --> 01:30:40.480
[Guest]: shape that.

01:30:40.480 --> 01:30:47.680
[Guest]: So we do have a lot of Advaitic texts that are being circulated, but this isn't only

01:30:47.680 --> 01:30:48.680
[Guest]: happening in Persian.

01:30:48.680 --> 01:30:52.400
[Guest]: So what's happening in Persian also mirrors what is happening in Hindavi.

01:30:52.400 --> 01:31:00.320
[Guest]: So we have this whole series of Braj Bhasha translations of Advaitic texts that become

01:31:00.320 --> 01:31:01.320
[Guest]: really popular.

01:31:01.320 --> 01:31:06.360
[Guest]: So we have a kind of vernacularization of Vedanta and Persian is contributing to and

01:31:06.360 --> 01:31:12.160
[Guest]: mirroring this trend, but all of this is laying the groundwork for Vedanta being seen as the

01:31:12.160 --> 01:31:14.760
[Guest]: kind of essence of Hinduism later on.

01:31:14.760 --> 01:31:19.880
[Guest]: So we have the popularization of Vedanta that is taking place and Persian is a major driver

01:31:19.880 --> 01:31:20.880
[Guest]: for that.

01:31:20.880 --> 01:31:28.520
[Guest]: And I don't know how, to what extent Persian is being seen as a foreign language, you know,

01:31:28.520 --> 01:31:33.200
[Guest]: by some perhaps, but by others, you know, they are very, very comfortable with it.

01:31:33.200 --> 01:31:35.080
[Guest]: Just like English, for instance.

01:31:35.080 --> 01:31:36.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's what I was going to say.

01:31:36.560 --> 01:31:41.280
[Amit Varma]: Much as English is very much an Indian language today, so no one should complain about words

01:31:41.280 --> 01:31:42.560
[Amit Varma]: like preporn.

01:31:42.560 --> 01:31:46.440
[Amit Varma]: And question I'll ask about this project then, I mean, it sounds incredibly fascinating and

01:31:46.440 --> 01:31:51.880
[Amit Varma]: I wasn't aware that Persian was so widely used within the subcontinent by people who

01:31:51.880 --> 01:31:57.360
[Amit Varma]: weren't part of the empire per se, but then what's the broad aha moment there?

01:31:57.360 --> 01:32:00.040
[Amit Varma]: What drove you to the project and what excited you about it?

01:32:00.040 --> 01:32:05.040
[Guest]: Well, one of the things that drove me to this was when you look at figures who seem to be

01:32:05.040 --> 01:32:10.800
[Guest]: really key to the evolution of modern Hindu thought, like Radha Ram Mohan Roy, you know,

01:32:10.800 --> 01:32:15.720
[Guest]: his initial writings, his initial book, the Tawfat al Mawahidin, is in Persian, you know,

01:32:15.720 --> 01:32:17.440
[Guest]: with an Arabic introduction.

01:32:17.440 --> 01:32:22.040
[Guest]: It was initially written in Persian, you know, I found that that work is in dialogue with

01:32:22.040 --> 01:32:27.240
[Guest]: the writings of various other Hindus and Muslims, you know, people who considered themselves

01:32:27.240 --> 01:32:32.200
[Guest]: kind of sort of freethinkers, but who were very also not shaped by the colonial context

01:32:32.200 --> 01:32:35.560
[Guest]: who are resident in Banaras and he's supposed to have traveled to Banaras.

01:32:35.560 --> 01:32:40.480
[Guest]: So I find that it definitely gives an interesting window onto this.

01:32:40.480 --> 01:32:46.720
[Guest]: One of the ways in which I'm personally interested in the study is that among scholars of the

01:32:46.720 --> 01:32:50.040
[Guest]: field, there is this perennial debate about Hinduism.

01:32:50.040 --> 01:32:55.080
[Guest]: And this is something that, you know, no doubt would seem really shocking to many people

01:32:55.080 --> 01:32:58.280
[Guest]: in India, people who might consider themselves Hindus.

01:32:58.280 --> 01:33:02.680
[Guest]: And the debate is really about whether Hinduism, of course, the English term Hinduism is something

01:33:02.680 --> 01:33:05.800
[Guest]: that's pretty modern, you know, from the 18th century.

01:33:05.800 --> 01:33:12.080
[Guest]: Is this something that was really shaped and formed under colonial rule?

01:33:12.080 --> 01:33:13.640
[Guest]: Or is this something that existed earlier?

01:33:13.640 --> 01:33:19.080
[Guest]: You know, there are some scholars of colonialism who are using this not as a way to critique

01:33:19.080 --> 01:33:26.920
[Guest]: Indian religions per se, but as a way of critiquing colonialism, showing how the colonial authorities

01:33:26.920 --> 01:33:33.920
[Guest]: try to reshape religions, erect strict boundaries around communities, formed these really as

01:33:33.920 --> 01:33:39.400
[Guest]: kind of visualized communities and attributed to them, you know, in essence.

01:33:39.400 --> 01:33:43.320
[Guest]: So some of this might have been done in a slightly more admiring fashion.

01:33:43.320 --> 01:33:46.920
[Guest]: Other part of this project might have been done in a more denigrating fashion.

01:33:46.920 --> 01:33:50.320
[Guest]: We have Orientalists who admired aspects of what they studied.

01:33:50.320 --> 01:33:53.800
[Guest]: We have others who thought this was all just all terrible.

01:33:53.800 --> 01:34:00.520
[Guest]: So there is one argument that is really strongly in favor of the colonial construction of Hinduism.

01:34:00.520 --> 01:34:05.080
[Guest]: And those who study the pre-modern period find that no matter what you study, you can

01:34:05.080 --> 01:34:08.440
[Guest]: always find some early antecedents for this.

01:34:08.440 --> 01:34:14.040
[Guest]: You can find antecedents for a kind of Hindu consolidation if you study Indian philosophy,

01:34:14.040 --> 01:34:15.040
[Guest]: for instance.

01:34:15.040 --> 01:34:19.720
[Guest]: But there's a consolidation of the aspects, you know, against the Gnostics, for instance.

01:34:19.720 --> 01:34:21.400
[Guest]: Well, why did this happen?

01:34:21.400 --> 01:34:26.280
[Guest]: It's not something that's very immediately apparent, but it, you know, it could be that

01:34:26.280 --> 01:34:32.760
[Guest]: having Muslim rulers or an Islamic presence indirectly kind of nudged a unification or

01:34:32.760 --> 01:34:36.560
[Guest]: a consolidation of these philosophical schools.

01:34:36.560 --> 01:34:39.080
[Guest]: So it's a perennial question that people are debating.

01:34:39.080 --> 01:34:45.400
[Guest]: And one of the actual links between the pre-colonial and the colonial period is Persian, because

01:34:45.400 --> 01:34:52.160
[Guest]: that's a bridged language and a whole kind of view on a cultural world that we find operating

01:34:52.160 --> 01:34:57.080
[Guest]: seamlessly through the transition from pre-colonial to colonial rule.

01:34:57.080 --> 01:35:01.360
[Amit Varma]: There's a fascinating book about this called, I think, The Truth About Us by Sanjay Chakraborty.

01:35:01.360 --> 01:35:06.600
[Amit Varma]: And I also discussed it with Manu Pillay in an old episode where, yeah, I mean, the broad

01:35:06.600 --> 01:35:12.800
[Amit Varma]: sense that I had of this period of time and how or what we know as Hinduism as a concept

01:35:12.800 --> 01:35:17.560
[Amit Varma]: came about was that, look, the British land up in India and they don't understand the

01:35:17.560 --> 01:35:18.560
[Amit Varma]: language.

01:35:18.560 --> 01:35:19.560
[Amit Varma]: They don't understand anything.

01:35:19.560 --> 01:35:21.480
[Amit Varma]: They want to make sense of a complex world.

01:35:21.480 --> 01:35:23.240
[Amit Varma]: They need a simple narrative.

01:35:23.240 --> 01:35:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Their early interlocutors are these upper caste Brahmins who give them their version

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:33.840
[Amit Varma]: of what how society is structured and the varna system is very much part of that.

01:35:33.840 --> 01:35:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And that kind of one sided view, it forms a convenient narrative through which you view

01:35:37.600 --> 01:35:42.360
[Amit Varma]: this exotic land and begin to navigate, you know, Indian society.

01:35:42.360 --> 01:35:44.280
[Amit Varma]: And that becomes the narrative.

01:35:44.280 --> 01:35:49.320
[Amit Varma]: And oddly enough, this mistaken narrative by, you know, our colonial rulers becomes

01:35:49.320 --> 01:35:55.120
[Amit Varma]: the narrative that then seeps into all of our culture and gets widely accepted.

01:35:55.120 --> 01:35:59.840
[Amit Varma]: And regardless of what the intent might be of the British, whether this was a deliberate

01:35:59.840 --> 01:36:03.960
[Amit Varma]: way or and it played into the divide and rule or whether it was unwitting and they were

01:36:03.960 --> 01:36:07.180
[Amit Varma]: just trying to what the hell makes sense of the world, how else could they do it?

01:36:07.180 --> 01:36:10.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, but it strikes me while you were speaking just now that intellectual histories

01:36:10.880 --> 01:36:16.400
[Amit Varma]: of a period like that must be way more complex than this period, because there are, again,

01:36:16.400 --> 01:36:18.800
[Amit Varma]: so many languages in play.

01:36:18.800 --> 01:36:22.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I had no idea that Persian was such a big part of all of this.

01:36:22.480 --> 01:36:27.560
[Amit Varma]: And is the Persian literature of the time then also playing a part in narratives like

01:36:27.560 --> 01:36:29.840
[Guest]: this being built and propagated?

01:36:29.840 --> 01:36:30.840
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:36:30.840 --> 01:36:34.720
[Guest]: In the 18th century, there was more Persian being produced in India than in Iraq.

01:36:34.720 --> 01:36:36.760
[Guest]: Again, you're absolutely right.

01:36:36.760 --> 01:36:39.280
[Guest]: It's hard to do justice to all the different languages.

01:36:39.280 --> 01:36:43.560
[Guest]: You know, there was again, there was development and innovation in Sanskrit as well.

01:36:43.560 --> 01:36:46.920
[Guest]: You know, there's one narrative that, you know, Sanskrit kind of like dies out.

01:36:46.920 --> 01:36:48.880
[Guest]: There's nothing much new that's done in it.

01:36:48.880 --> 01:36:54.240
[Guest]: But scholars have shown that the 18th century, far from being a kind of a period of darkness

01:36:54.240 --> 01:37:01.160
[Guest]: and dissolution, was really a period of great cultural vibrancy at the time of political

01:37:01.160 --> 01:37:05.280
[Guest]: crisis and turmoil also partly perhaps as a result of that.

01:37:05.280 --> 01:37:12.000
[Guest]: So Persian is one aspect of it, and what I find that, you know, even after the colonial

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:18.040
[Guest]: government abandons it as an official language and abandons some of its earlier interest

01:37:18.040 --> 01:37:22.320
[Guest]: in Orientalism and producing scholarship on India, they kind of, you know, this is like

01:37:22.320 --> 01:37:25.920
[Guest]: more of the Macaulay influence that we see popping up.

01:37:25.920 --> 01:37:27.200
[Guest]: It doesn't really die.

01:37:27.200 --> 01:37:30.920
[Guest]: We have these generations of people who were educated in Persian.

01:37:30.920 --> 01:37:34.800
[Guest]: They learned Persian because they also want to get jobs in the colonial administration.

01:37:34.800 --> 01:37:37.800
[Guest]: And then they find it doesn't quite serve them as well.

01:37:37.800 --> 01:37:39.760
[Guest]: But they're producing these books.

01:37:39.760 --> 01:37:46.920
[Guest]: And with the growth of the Hindu public sphere, you have a lot of reformists who are translating

01:37:46.920 --> 01:37:51.520
[Guest]: these Persian works into Urdu, because now Urdu is what is more commonly understood.

01:37:51.520 --> 01:37:58.240
[Guest]: And these languages still don't have the kind of communal charges that they have today.

01:37:58.240 --> 01:38:03.360
[Guest]: So again, although there was beginnings of the Urdu-Hindu controversy in the 19th century,

01:38:03.360 --> 01:38:04.920
[Guest]: it doesn't always play out that way.

01:38:04.920 --> 01:38:08.880
[Guest]: You know, in Punjab, for instance, loads of Hindus were learning Urdu, and part of the

01:38:08.880 --> 01:38:12.440
[Guest]: education policy meant that Urdu really continued there for a long time.

01:38:12.440 --> 01:38:22.080
[Guest]: So we have people who are proto-Arya Samajis, proto kind of part of groups that, the Sanatan

01:38:22.080 --> 01:38:23.080
[Guest]: Dharm groups.

01:38:23.080 --> 01:38:27.320
[Guest]: He has debates with each other, and these debates are in a very Persianized register

01:38:27.320 --> 01:38:28.320
[Guest]: of Urdu.

01:38:28.320 --> 01:38:32.720
[Guest]: And they're debating and talking about things that, you know, we'd really get into trouble

01:38:32.720 --> 01:38:37.720
[Guest]: for if we were to debate or talk about these things today, but they're doing that.

01:38:37.720 --> 01:38:43.040
[Guest]: There's just reels of really fascinating literature that would otherwise be ignored.

01:38:43.040 --> 01:38:48.080
[Amit Varma]: And some of these intellectual currents that you're exploring, is it also driven by what

01:38:48.080 --> 01:38:50.400
[Amit Varma]: is happening in modern times?

01:38:50.400 --> 01:38:53.640
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, both what you're talking about now and the whole Dara Shikoh book is

01:38:53.640 --> 01:38:59.200
[Amit Varma]: very resonant with the sort of debates that are taking place today, our different sort

01:38:59.200 --> 01:39:02.040
[Amit Varma]: of our ideas of ourselves, so to say.

01:39:02.040 --> 01:39:07.480
[Amit Varma]: So is all of this driven by that and made more, and is that history or the writings

01:39:07.480 --> 01:39:12.600
[Amit Varma]: of that time made more vivid for you because of sort of the world around us?

01:39:12.600 --> 01:39:13.600
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:39:13.600 --> 01:39:18.880
[Guest]: So I would say that, of course, when I started on this path, we were not in our current political

01:39:18.880 --> 01:39:20.120
[Guest]: scenario at all.

01:39:20.120 --> 01:39:25.880
[Guest]: So that wasn't my initial impetus, but you know, definitely how can we are shaped by

01:39:25.880 --> 01:39:28.720
[Guest]: our current times that affects how we view the past.

01:39:28.720 --> 01:39:32.520
[Guest]: So it's, I'd say it's very, very difficult to step out of that.

01:39:32.520 --> 01:39:37.200
[Guest]: You know, there's some more, of course, profound questions that I have that I didn't have when

01:39:37.200 --> 01:39:41.200
[Guest]: I initially started on this path, which is, you know, of course, the ecological catastrophe

01:39:41.200 --> 01:39:46.320
[Guest]: in one's thinking of what is really worth studying now, you know, with the Anthropocene,

01:39:46.320 --> 01:39:52.640
[Guest]: with this ecological crisis, you know, what should we be doing with our lives?

01:39:52.640 --> 01:39:56.560
[Guest]: What kinds of history are worth reading and talking about?

01:39:56.560 --> 01:40:01.920
[Guest]: But I think it's not, you know, apart from the actual topic, I think just the very practice

01:40:01.920 --> 01:40:08.000
[Guest]: of reading, critically interrogating, debating, discussing are incredibly important things

01:40:08.000 --> 01:40:11.120
[Guest]: that we need to just keep doing, I'd say.

01:40:11.120 --> 01:40:12.600
[Amit Varma]: I can agree with you more.

01:40:12.600 --> 01:40:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for coming on the show, Supriya.

01:40:14.000 --> 01:40:15.480
[Amit Varma]: It's been a pleasure talking to you.

01:40:15.480 --> 01:40:18.880
[Guest]: Thank you so much, Amit.

01:40:18.880 --> 01:40:22.720
